<HEADLINE> Red Cross Seeks Financial Aid for Chernobyl Victims </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
GENEVA, November 11 (Xinhua) -- The Geneva-based International
Federation of Red Cross and Red Crescent Societies launched here
today an appeal seeking 1.3 million Swiss francs (about 0.92
million US dollars) for its humanitarian assistance to Chernobyl
victims.
</P>
<P>
More than 11 years after the world's worst technological
accident at the Chernobyl nuclear power plant in the former Soviet
Union, hundreds of thousands of people in Belarus, Ukraine and
Russia are still suffering from the consequences of Chernobyl, the
federation said in its press release.
</P>
<P>
"The incidence of thyroid gland cancer is rising, in particular
among children," the federation said. "A further rise is
expected."
</P>
<P>
Since 1986, around 1,000 children in the three countries have
been confirmed to have thyroid gland cancer, a spokesman for the
federation said.
</P>
<P>
Since 1992, the Red Cross has run six mobile diagnostic
laboratories to measure radioactivity in the environment and to
examine people's general health, which includes scanning for
thyroid irregularities.
</P>
<P>
The appeal today is looking for funds to help 200,000 people
for another year. "We need to find long-term solutions for
long-term problems," said Dr Jean-Pierre Revel of the federation's
relief health department. It is seeking funds for the new few
years before handing the program over to the Red Cross societies
in the three countries. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
