<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Philippine Parliament to Pass New Oil Deregulation Bill </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MANILA, November 11 (Xinhua) -- The Philippine Congress will
speed up the passage of a new oil deregulation law to save the
country's liberalized oil industry, which will have to be
regulated again under an earlier ruling from the Supreme Court.
</P>
<P>
Senate Majority Leader Francisco Tatad said today that the
Senate leadership has promised to President Fidel Ramos to step up
the drafting of a new oil deregulation bill.
</P>
<P>
Earlier last week, the Supreme Court overwhelmingly ruled to
nullify the country's nine-month-old oil deregulation law on the
ground that it was unconstitutional.
</P>
<P>
The court said the law violates the constitution by allowing
the country's three dominant oil companies to gain monopoly of the
industry.
</P>
<P>
Tatad said the Senate Committee on Energy is expected to start
this week its hearing on a new deregulation bill he filed, along
with those filed by other senators.
</P>
<P>
With the Senate's commitment, Tatad said, the committee shall
speed up the study on the proposed new oil deregulation measure
and come up with a consolidated version of the bill in several
days.
</P>
<P>
"We expect to have a new oil deregulation law in place as soon
as the Supreme Court ruling becomes final and executory," he said.
</P>
<P>
Earlier, the House of Representatives also promised to push for
the quick passage of a new oil deregulation law of its own
version.
</P>
<P>
The high tribunal has given the government 15 days to file a
motion for reconsideration on its ruling on the oil deregulation
law.
</P>
<P>
The oil deregulation law is vital for the Philippines to be
free from the supervision of its economy by the International
Monetary Fund (IMF). A return to oil regulation will likely delay
the country's exit from the IMF control. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
