<HEADLINE> Ghana Warns of Rising Fraud in Gold Trade </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HARARE, November 11 (Xinhua) -- The Ghana government,
concerned with rising fraud in the buying and selling of gold,
today warned through its high commission in Harare that foreign
dealers engaged in such practices risk being cheated.
</P>
<P>
Head of the high commission in Zimbabwe Awinador-Kanyirige
said in a statement that there was a misconception among
foreigners that gold could be bought at a significant discount in
the west African nation.
</P>
<P>
''It has come to the attention of the Ghana government that,
as a result of Ghana's favorable business climate and
international reputation as a major gold exporter, numerous
foreign companies and individuals have sought to get rich quick
through gold transactions,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
He said the price of gold in Ghana is comparable to world
prices, and advised that all small-holder purchases should be
conducted through the precious minerals marketing corporation.
</P>
<P>
Prospective buyers who conducted business outside the official
channels did so at their own risk, he said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
