<HEADLINE> Malaysia to Promote Economic Ties with Pakistan </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ISLAMABAD, November 11 (Xinhua) -- The Malaysian prime
minister's economic advisor Tim Daim Zainuddin said today his
country is keen to promote business and investment relations with
Pakistan.
</P>
<P>
Addressing the Chamber of Commerce and Industry in Lahore,
Zainuddin said Malaysia had introduced an interest-free economy in
order to establish the Islamic Monitory System.
</P>
<P>
The interest-free economy generates more profits and savings in
business activities, said Zainuddin, who is visiting Pakistan as
the head of an 11-member Malaysian trade delegation.
</P>
<P>
Talking about the Pakistani-Malaysian business relations,
Zaiuddin said the incentives and facilities offered by the
Pakistani government had attracted Malaysian entrepreneurs.
</P>
<P>
He hoped that a number of joint ventures in various industrial
and commercial sectors will be materialized in the due course.
</P>
<P>
Pakistan imported goods worth 14.26 billion rupees (about 325
million U.S. dollars) from Malaysia in 1996-97, while its exports
to Malaysia in the same period were worth only 840 million rupees
(19 million dollars).  
</P>
</TEXT>
