<DATE_TIME> 1997-11-11 16:11 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> FM: Canada Supports UN Actions Against Iraq </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JERUSALEM, November 11 (Xinhua) -- Canada today expressed its
support for the United Nations to take firm actions against Iraq
over the current crisis.
</P>
<P>
Iraq should honor its obligations and respect to the U.N.
Security Council resolutions, Canadian Foreign Minister Lloyd
Axworthy said at a joint press conference here with Israeli
Foreign Minister David Levy after their talks.
</P>
<P>
"We're steadfast in our support for the U.N. position.... We
want to see the U.N. take firm actions to ensure that the Iraqis
live up to their obligations and the resolutions," Axworthy said.
</P>
<P>
Iraq's decision on October 29 to expel American inspectors on
the U.N. weapons inspection teams overseeing the disarmament of
Iraq has incurred a crisis between Iraq and the U.N. as well as
the United States.
</P>
<P>
During their talks, Axworthy and Levy discussed wide range of
issues concerning bilateral ties, Israel's participation in the
upcoming anti-mine conference in Canadian capital Ottawa and the
Middle East peace process.
</P>
<P>
The Israeli-Canadian relations were soured in late September
when two Israeli agents using forged Canadian passports carried
out a failed assassination attempt against Hamas political leader
Khaled Mashaal in Amman.
</P>
<P>
Canada lodged a protest by recalling its ambassador to Israel,
which took quick actions to remedy the ties. Levy sent a formal
apology to Axworthy in early October for the affair.
</P>
<P>
Axworthy said that he got clear assurance from Levy today to
prevent such incident from happening again.
</P>
<P>
Axworthy praised Israel's decision to attend the Ottawa
anti-mine conference next month as a serious effort to eliminate
mines.
</P>
<P>
The Canadian minister arrived here today for a one-day visit.
He will later travel to Turkey, and then Qatar to attend the
Middle East and North Africa economic conference on November
16-18. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
