<HEADLINE> China Anticipates Closer Worldwide Economic Ties </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, November 11 (Xinhua) -- Chinese Vice-Premier Li
Lanqing said here today that China plans to establish closer
economic ties worldwide in the 21st century.
</P>
<P>
Li, who also serves as a member of the Standing Committee of
the Political Bureau of the Central Committee of the Chinese
Communist Party, made the
remarks during an international symposium on investment
policy and investment risk insurance.
</P>
<P>
The vice-premier noted that China is a driving force in
worldwide trade and economic development. He noted that China's
import and export volume hit 289 billion US dollars in 1996, and
ranked 11th amongst the world's major trading nations.
</P>
<P>
China's vast potential market, one of the most attractive
in the world, has attracted foreign funds of over 320
billion US dollars, including some 200 billion US dollars
in foreign direct investment.
</P>
<P>
The Chinese government had approved the establishment of some
300,000 foreign-funded enterprises by the end of 1996.
</P>
<P>
Li projected that the country's total import and export volume
will hit 310 billion US dollars by the end of this year, with
foreign direct investments expected to surpass 43 billion US
dollars.
</P>
<P>
He predicted that China's import and export volume will top 400
billion US dollars by the year 2000, a fact which will vigorously
promote world trade and economic development, and will at the same
time create wide-ranging opportunities for cooperation between
China and other countries.
</P>
<P>
Today's symposium, sponsored by the State Planning
Commission, attracted representatives from 20 countries and
regions, including the United States, France, Germany and Japan.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
