<HEADLINE> New HIV Genotype Found in Nigeria </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LAGOS, November 11 (Xinhua) -- A new genotype of the human
deficiency virus (HIV), which cause the dreaded acquired immuned
deficiency symdrone (AIDS), has been found in Nigeria, the
Guardian reported today.
</P>
<P>
The newspaper quoted chief epidemiologist Abdulsalam Nasidi as
saying that the government is trying to identify the new genotype
which was previously unknown with the assistance of some foreign
scientists.
</P>
<P>
The strange genotype was found in Lagos, the largest city of
the country in the southwest, and Maiduguri, capital of Borno
state in the northeast.
</P>
<P>
Nasidi's disclosure at a national symposium on HIV and AIDS on
Monday came amid worries expressed by medical scientists about
rising AIDS pandemic in Nigeria in face of government's weak
control program.
</P>
<P>
He said Nigeria had the opportunity to devise formidable plan
of action between 1986 nd 1990 when the disease was still at its
formative stage but it failed to do so.
</P>
<P>
The incidence of AIDS had increased by 500 fold in the country
between 1986 and last year, he said.
</P>
<P>
He did not disclose the figure of AIDS cases across the
country.
</P>
<P>
However, Kenneth Oforu-Barko, representative of a joint United
Nations program on HIV/AIDS in Nigeria, said acumulative 10,803
AIDS cases had been reported in the country to the national
AIDS/STD control program.
</P>
<P>
Barko predicted that there should be less than 364,286
cumulative cases of AIDS in the country by the year 2000 and that
the cumulative deaths from AIDS could be 304,285.
</P>
<P>
According to him, there are an estimated 2.2 million of the
100 million Nigerians living with HIV, while 103,580 deaths will
occur from AIDS this year alone, which could be translated to 284
per day.
</P>
<P>
He called for research in molecular epidemiology of HIV, and
vaccines as well as social, operation and evaluative research as
a means of combating the pandemic. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
