<HEADLINE> New Irish President Appeals for Ulster Peace </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LONDON, November 11 (Xinhua) -- New Irish President Mary
McAleese has promised to do her best to help bring a long lasting
peace to the British-ruled Northern Ireland, said reports from
Dublin.
</P>
<P>
Speaking in an inauguration address at the Dublin Castle,
McAleese, who is the first ever Irish head of state born in
Northern Ireland, said that the theme of her presidency would be
building bridges between conflicting communities.
</P>
<P>
"We hope and pray, indeed we insist, that we have seen the last
of violence. We demand the right to solve our problems by dialogue
and the noble pursuit of consensus," She said.
</P>
<P>
McAleese, who once said she had deep regard to those
pro-British Protestants, also called for real reconciliation of
the Irish Catholics and British Protestants. "No side has a
monopoly on pain. Each has suffered intensely," she said.
</P>
<P>
Irish Prime Minister Bertie Ahern said that the new presidency
was "a symbol of inclusiveness and deeper understanding and of a
firm desire on the part of all our people to move away from the
hurtful conflict of the past." 
</P>
</TEXT>
