<HEADLINE> Canada Likely to Reap Budget Surplus This Year </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
OTTAWA, November 11 (Xinhua) -- Canada's federal government is
on track this year to post its first annual budget surplus in
nearly three decades, said reports today.
</P>
<P>
Finance Department figures showed that Ottawa racked up a 2
billion dollar (1.4 billion US dollar) surplus in September,
leaving it 1.7 billion dollars in the black for the first half of
the 1997-98 fiscal year.
</P>
<P>
That represented Canada's first six-month budgetary surplus in
at least 25 years, the reports said.
</P>
<P>
For the same period last year, Ottawa got a deficit of 7
billion dollars.
</P>
<P>
Finance Minister Paul Martin said last month that the
government would balance its budget no later than next year.
</P>
<P>
But Prime Minister Jean Chretien has since said that his
government could eliminate the deficit as early as this year.
</P>
<P>
Ottawa posted an 8.9 billion dollar deficit last year.
</P>
<P>
The department cautioned against using the results of the first
six months to forecast a surplus for the whole fiscal year.
</P>
<P>
There have been some extra revenue gains in the first half of
the year that won't be available in the second half, such as
additional employment-insurance premiums, the department noted.
</P>
</TEXT>
