<HEADLINE> Japan, China Issue Joint Declaration on WTO Talks </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
TOKYO, November 11 (Xinhua) -- Japan and China issued a joint
declaration here today announcing "major advancement" in some
aspects of the talks on China's entry into the World Trade
Organization (WTO).
</P>
<P>
The declaration was jointly issued by Koichi Haraguchi,
director-general of the economic affairs bureau of the Japanese
foreign ministry, and Long Yongtu, chief negotiator for the
Chinese Ministry of Foreign Trade and Economic Cooperation.
</P>
<P>
In the past few months, the declaration said, Chinese and
Japanese negotiators held extensive and in-depth talks on the
suggestions made by China on service trade.
</P>
<P>
Such talks touched upon many areas in which the Japanese side
has interests, such as sales service, financial service,
telecommunications service, transportation service, construction
and real estate service, accounting and legal service.
</P>
<P>
The Japanese side expressed admiration to the Chinese side for
its arduous effort, said the declaration.
</P>
<P>
The chief negotiators believed that the two sides have scored
"major advances" at their talks on service trade, and are working
together to complete the talks, the declaration said.
</P>
<P>
The two sides agreed that China's entry into the WTO will
benefit not only both countries, but all WTO members, the
declaration noted.
</P>
<P>
The two sides reiterated their determination to work closely at
the talks of the working groups in Geneva so as to assist China in
entering the WTO at an early date, the declaration added.
</P>
<P>
The declaration said both sides believe cooperation between
China and Japan at the WTO talks will contribute to the further
enhancement of long-term and stable economic ties between the two
countries.
</P>
<P>
Chinese Premier Li Peng arrived in Tokyo this afternoon for a
six-day official good-will visit to Japan. Long Yongtu is one of
the key members of Li's entourage. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
