<HEADLINE> German Tax Gap to Be 17.3 Billion Marks in 1997 </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BONN, November 11 (Xinhua) -- Germany would face a huge
shortfall of 17.3 billion marks (10 billion U.S. dollars) in tax
revenues in 1997, the German Finance Ministry confirmed today.
</P>
<P>
According to the latest projections by a government-appointed
tax estimate group, the gap in government tax revenues would widen
further to 22.4 billion marks (13 billion dollars) in 1998, the
ministry added.
</P>
<P>
However, officials of the ministry were also quoted by the
German media as saying that despite the declining tax revenues,
the country's total budget deficit this year would be about 72
billion marks ((42 billion dollars), only slightly above the
planned level of 71.2 billion marks.
</P>
<P>
German Finance Minister Theo Waigel today also said in Bonn
that Germany would still be able to meet the budget target of the
single European currency, which requires a European Union country
to bring its budget deficit to less than 3 percent of the gross
domestic product (GDP) in order to qualify for its membership.
</P>
<P>
Waigel was scheduled to make a statement later today to say
what the government will undertake to try to close the financial
gaps. 
</P>
</TEXT>
