<DATE_TIME> 1997-11-12 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Floods Wreak Havoc on Somali Town </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MOGADISHU, November 11 (Xinhua) -- The central town of
Beledweyne has been plagued by floods from the Shabelle River
that burst its banks and poured into town yesterday.
</P>
<P>
The inhabitants of Beledweyne Town, 300 km north of the
capital, have moved their children and precious pieces of
property to the nearby mountains that surround the town.
</P>
<P>
According to regional governor of Hiran, Hassan Abdulle Qalad,
the fate of more than 170 patients who were in the main hospital
of the town is not known after the floods had suddenly poured
into the area.
</P>
<P>
Qalad added that the floods have also severely affected 35
villages that surround Beledweyne.
</P>
<P>
Beledweyne, the largest flood-affected town of the country so
far has now been out of reach since all the bridges that linked
the town, collapsed.
</P>
<P>
River Shabelle passes through the town twice in the shape of
"S", and it has first burst its bank in the Irid Amin area, north
of Beledweyne.
</P>
<P>
Qalad disclosed that 15 families are so far known to have
drowned in the waters, adding the people of the town are now
running short of food and have no shelter at all on the hilly
side.
</P>
<P>
Qalad urged the international aid agencies to bring relief to
the victims of Hiran, saying motor boats, tents, medicine and
food are urgently needed. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
