<HEADLINE> Malaysia Urged to Relocate Labor-Intensive Industries </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ISLAMABAD, November 11 (Xinhua) -- Pakistan's Minister for
Commerce and Investment Ishaq Dar today called on Malaysia to
relocate their labor-intensive industries into Pakistan.
</P>
<P>
Dar made the call during a meeting with a visiting Malaysian
trade delegation led by Economic Advisor to the Malaysian Prime
Minister Tun Daim Zainuddin.
</P>
<P>
Dar said Pakistan provides not only a large local consumer
market but also easy access to Central Asian and Middle East
markets.
</P>
<P>
He also explained various incentives given by the Pakistani
government to foreign investors and said foreign investment enjoys
full protection in Pakistan under the law.
</P>
<P>
Zainuddin expressed the Malaysian private sector's desire to
invest in Pakistan and also to expand bilateral trade.
</P>
<P>
The delegation consists of leading Malaysian firms in the
fields of engineering, construction, property development,
telecommunications, mining, financial services, ship building,
hotels, resort &AMP; recreation development, textile and trading.
</P>
