<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Zimbabwe's Vegetable Growers Eye Export Market </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HARARE, November 11 (Xinhua) -- The recently formed Fresh
Produce Producers Association (FPAP) today predicted a 30 percent
increase in export sales during the 1997/98 season, up from
11,000 tons last year.
</P>
<P>
FPAP Chief Executive Pat Henson said local demand for their
produce is even higher than on the international market due to
stiff competition in the tourism industry.
</P>
<P>
Hotels and restaurants are constantly introducing new dishes
to attract customers.
</P>
<P>
"We earned about 325 million Zimbabwe Dollars (26 million U.S.
Dollars) from fresh produce last year and even more was expected
this year," she said.
</P>
<P>
Products include tomatoes, onions, peas, beans, paprika and a
wide range of green vegetables.
</P>
<P>
She said there is great export potential, particularly in the
United Kingdom.
</P>
<P>
She said she has compiled a list of fresh produce pack houses
and is currently liaisoning with the produce marketing of Zimbabwe
on promotional activities. 
</P>
