<DATE_TIME> 1997-11-12 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Britain Sets Out 3 Pillars for Competitiveness </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BIRMINGHAM, November 11 (Xinhua) -- Strong markets, modern
companies and looking to the future are the three pillars of
Britain's new approach to competitive success, Margaret Beckett,
president of the Board of Trade, said today.
</P>
<P>
Beckett told the Confederation of British Industry's (CBI)
Annual Conference, "We must tread a fresh path -- neither too much
interference nor the neglect of sheer indifference -- but a new
third way."
</P>
<P>
The three pillars are the themes which bind all of the
activities of the Department of Trade and Industry to the pursuit
of competitiveness and against which the department will measure
the worth and relevance of those activities, Beckett added.
</P>
<P>
On strong markets, she said that a strong competition policy is
fundamental to competitiveness. That's why one of the government's
earliest actions was to find for a Competition Bill and search for
greater transparency, predictability and consistency in
regulation.
</P>
<P>
Referring to modern companies, Beckett said that only modern
companies can address modern challenges. Modern companies
succeeding in new markets with new products -- companies that are
competing on strengths in design, in science, in ideas -- not on
cheap labor.
</P>
<P>
Beckett also set out her views on corporate governance: "We
want forms of governance and company law that encourage companies
to invest and grow to take the long term strategic view and a
broad view of their obligations."
</P>
<P>
She said that they should also guarantee openness, transparency
and accountability, not least in the relationship between
shareholders and management.
</P>
<P>
On looking to the future, she said that the Labor government
can help or hinder the development of new firms, new ideas -- keep
them here or let them drift abroad.
</P>
<P>
Beckett suggested that the government must embrace the
industries of the future and in particular it must address the
specific needs of smaller firms. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19971112.0021 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-11-12 </DATE_TIME>
