<HEADLINE> Turkey's Islamic Party to Defend against Closure </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ANKARA, November 11 (Xinhua) -- Necmettin Erbakan, chairman of
Turkey's pro-Islamic Welfare Party (RP), will deliver a verbal
statement to the Constitutional Court next week to defend agaisnt
a closure case concerning his party.
</P>
<P>
Erbakan came to the court earlier today but failed to make the
statement as planned. The reason remained unknown.
</P>
<P>
RP Deputy Chairman Sevket Kazan announced to the press in the
court that Erbakan would defend for his party on November 18, the
Anatolia News Agency reported.
</P>
<P>
Turkey's Chief Prosecutor Vural Savas filed a case with the
Constitutional Court in May demanding the Islamist party be shut
down on the grounds of its support for fundamentalism.
</P>
<P>
Erbakan resigned as prime minister in June under pressure from
the pro-secular military which criticized him for his reluctance
to take tough measures against fundamentalism.
</P>
<P>
The legal procedures of the closure case will be completed and
the court will render its ruling after Erbakan delivers his verbal
statement.
</P>
<P>
According to Turkey' Party Law, Erbakan and some senior RP
officials will be banned from engaging in politics for at least
five years if the party is outlawed. 
</P>
</TEXT>
