<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Mercedes Suspends Delivery on New A-Class Car </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BONN, November 11 (Xinhua) -- The German carmaker Mercedes-Benz
is halting the delivery on its controversial new A-class compact
for 12 weeks for modification of the car's suspension regulation
system, its parent company Daimler-Benz announced today.
</P>
<P>
The Stuttgart-based firm assured that the modifications would
cure the problem causing the newly-introduced car to roll over
when radically swerving to avoid road obstacles during a test in
Sweden last month.
</P>
<P>
Daimler said the modifications would include news stabilizers
and a retuning of the springs and shock absorbers with the axles.
Also, a different tire would be adopted and the car body work
would be lowered.
</P>
<P>
Two weeks ago the company said that all the sold 3,000 A-class
models would also be modified, but did not specify its plan to
recall them.
</P>
<P>
Daily output of the A-class model stands currently at 200
units, and will be raised to 800 in February, according to
Daimler.
</P>
<P>
The five-door A-class model represents Mercedes' first entry
into compact-category and is designed to compete with the
bestselling Volkswagen's Golf. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
