<DATE_TIME> 1997-11-12 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Tough Decisions on Spending, Borrowing: CBI </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BIRMINGHAM, November 11 (Xinhua) -- The government should set a
firm ceiling of 40 percent GDP on the amount of public spending
paid for by taxes and government borrowing, according to a
Confederation of British Industry (CBI) paper out today.
</P>
<P>
In a discussion document on government expenditure and
borrowing, the CBI set out some options for the tough decisions
that the government needs to make.
</P>
<P>
There is a sound economic case for limiting the percentage of
public spending raised through taxes, and also for keeping public
borrowing within limits, the document added.
</P>
<P>
Andrew Buxton, chairman of the CBI's Economic Affairs
Committee, said at the closing session of the CBI conference, "The
government faces difficult choices as it seeks to balance the
growing demand for public services with the need to keep down
public borrowing and tax rises."
</P>
<P>
"The government should consider extending new ways of paying
for services to allow funding for education and transport to rise
in real terms," he added.
</P>
<P>
The CBI accepted that it has not been easy to keep down public
spending, but Britain has done well compared with the rest of
Europe.
</P>
<P>
It recommended that the government's current plans to contain
public spending should be sufficiently tight but meeting these
plans is likely to prove a demanding task. 
</P>
</TEXT>
