<HEADLINE> Canada on Verge of Postal Strike </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
OTTAWA, November 11 (Xinhua) -- Canada is on the verge of its
first postal strike in six years as Canada Post and postal workers
count down to the deadline of midnight Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
Talks broke off on the weekend, but both parties hope to resume
discussions before time runs out.
</P>
<P>
"As it stands now, we are on 24-hour standby, ready and willing
to negotiate," said Darrell Tingley, head of the Canadian Union of
Postal Workers.
</P>
<P>
"We can't continue to talk to ourselves," said a spokesman of
the corporation.
</P>
<P>
Talks stalled as the two sides could not reach agreement on the
proposed 200 million dollar (140 million US dollar) reduction in
labor costs and wage increases.
</P>
<P>
The union said the reduction will mean 4,000 jobs lost, while
the corporation insisted no one will lose their job because work
rules can be adjusted to save money.
</P>
<P>
The union is asking for wage increases of more than 8 percent
over 18 months, while Canada Post is offering increases of 3
percent over two years.
</P>
<P>
The two sides are so far apart they need the threat of a strike
or lockout to reach an agreement, said the conciliator appointed
to help settle the labor dispute. 
</P>
</TEXT>
