<HEADLINE> Angolan Ruling Party Calls for Peace </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LUANDA, November 11 (Xinhua) -- The ruling Angolan People's
Liberation Movement (MPLA) today urged the government and
especially the former rebel UNITA movement to make greater effort
for the final peace in the country.
</P>
<P>
Marking the 22nd anniversary of the independence of Angola,
the ruling party said in a communique that the government and the
National Union for the Total Independence of Angola (UNITA)
should join hands to remove any obstacles to Angola's final
peace.
</P>
<P>
The party said it regretted that the threat of war is still
hanging over the country three years after the Lusaka Peace
Protocol was signed, saying that this situation bars the nation
and its citizens from devoting their energy fully to building the
country.
</P>
<P>
The statement said that to reach the goal mapped out by the
Lusaka accord, UNITA should carry out all the obligations as
outlined by the pact.
</P>
<P>
The Lusaka Peace Protocol stipulated that UNITA should disarm
its army entirely and hand over all its weapons to the U.N.
monitoring team, turn its radio station into a non-party
commercial one, and re-establish government institutions in areas
under its control and create conditions for free movement of
people in Angola.
</P>
<P>
The statement also urged that UNITA move its headquarters to
Luanda as soon as possible.
</P>
<P>
The communique, issued by the political bureau of the ruling
party, called on all Angolans to unite for the realization of
final peace in the country in a spirit of tolerance and mutual
support, so as to rid the country of its serious social and
economic crisis. 
</P>
</TEXT>
