<HEADLINE> Britons Turn to More Health-Conscious Diets: Survey </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LONDON, November 11 (Xinhua) -- British people have turned to
more health-conscious diets by eating more fruit and vegetables,
but less fat, according to the National Food Survey 1996.
</P>
<P>
The survey, published annually by the Ministry of Agriculture,
Fisheries and Food, showed that average consumption of fresh fruit
per head rose just under 3 percent in 1996 and was 17 percent
higher than 10 years ago.
</P>
<P>
The average consumption of vegetable per head was also up, by 4
percent excluding potatoes. However, it was still 9 percent lower
than in 1986 and people are eating less greens.
</P>
<P>
The survey said that the percentage of food energy provided by
fat was down a tenth of a percentage point, continuing its
long-term decline in the British diet.
</P>
<P>
The biggest decline in consumption last year was in beef and
veal, which was down 17 percent following the mad cow disease
scare. There was also an 8 percent fall in consumption of meat and
meat products eaten out.
</P>
<P>
However, fish consumption reached its highest level for more
than 20 years and there were also marked increases in consumption
of mutton, lamb and poultry. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19971112.0030 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-11-12 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Ethiopia Immunization Drive Targets at 8.6m </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ADDIS ABABA, November (Xinhua) -- The Nation-Wide Immunization
Days (NID) which will be launched in Ethiopia this week will
target 8.6 million children under the age of five, a senior
official said here today.
</P>
<P>
Adem Ibrahim, Ethiopian Minister of Health announced this at
a press conference on the NID here this afternoon.
</P>
<P>
Adem said this year's NID are conducted in the whole country
during November 13-16 with polio vaccine and on December 12-14
with polio vaccine and vitamin supplements.
</P>
<P>
A total of 25,487 posts will be prepared for this year's NID,
with 28,058 health staff and 51,681 volunteers involved, he said,
adding that each immunization post will be staffed with a minimum
of one health staff plus two volunteers.
</P>
<P>
Adem further said that the disease has now disappeared in 120
countries. However, it continues to affect and kill in some of
the poorest and more densely populated countries, he noted.
</P>
<P>
Referring to the situation in Ethiopia, Adem said, "it is
estimated (there are) 2,000 cases per year. Currently, there are
about 60,000 cases every year globally, and 12,000 in the African
continent."
</P>
<P>
This means that Ethiopia is contributing three percent and 17
percent of cases to the world and Africa respectively, he said.
</P>
<P>
Ethiopia has planned to eradicate polio by the year 2000. This
is the first nation-wide immunization campaign to be launched in
the country and the campaign will be conducted in all states,
regions and districts of Ethiopia.
</P>
<P>
Last year, the immunization days were launched in nine
selected urban areas with about 300,000 children under the age of
five years immunized against poliomyelitis.
</P>
<P>
Polio is an infectious disease caused by a virus doing harm to
the nervous system, affects mostly children, usually before 5
years of age.
</P>
<P>
The disease causes paralysis, usually of the legs, and
sometimes death. Paralysis begins rapidly in one or two days and
is permanent. There is no treatment, but it can be prevented
through immunization with oral polio vaccine. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19971112.0031 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-11-11 17:48 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> No Results Expected From Discussions in </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NICOSIA, November 11 (Xinhua) -- U.S. special envoy for Cyprus
Richard Holbrooke said here today that he did not expect any
results from his discussions with the two leaders of the two
communities in Cyprus.
</P>
<P>
He made the statement following a four-hour meeting with
Cypriot President Glafcos Clerides and Turkish Cypriot leader Rauf
Denktash, held at the Ledra Palace Hotel in the U.N.-controlled
buffer zone in Nicosia.
</P>
<P>
However, Holbrooke said he would leave the island "with a very
much improved understanding of the views of the two leaders."
</P>
<P>
He refrained from revealing what was discussed, saying that
"these were informal talks, we did not expect any results today
that would be substantive."
</P>
<P>
In response to local criticism that he is here to back
Clerides' candidacy in next February's presidential elections,
Holbrooke said "we are not here to involve ourselves in a domestic
political election in the Republic of Cyprus."
</P>
<P>
He said he discussed with the leaders of the two communities
the issues that have long divided this trouble island.
</P>
<P>
Replying to questions at a press conference, Holbrooke
described the discussions as "candid and confidential" and were
conducted in a very positive atmosphere.
</P>
<P>
Today's discussions, he added, showed a "willingness to try
to address the problems of the future."
</P>
<P>
He said he did not ask the two leaders for a commitment to
continue some kind of dialogue until March next year.
</P>
<P>
The differences between the two leaders in the island are very
profound and they range from very small details like the content
of documents to very basic issues like how to deal with the right
of refugees to return, Holbrooke said.
</P>
<P>
Defining his task in the peace effort, Holbrooke said the
U.S. believes this region is critical to stability for the
U.S. national security and the Europe.
</P>
<P>
"We believe that stability is an essential goal in the post
cold war period and in my view the other issues between Greece
and Turkey cannot be dealt with unless Cyprus is dealt with
centrally, it is the core issue," the U.S. envoy stressed.
</P>
<P>
Holbrooke noted that he would consult with U.S. ambassadors
in Nicosia, Ankara and Athens as well as U.S. President Bill
Clinton and Secretary of State Madeleine Albright before deciding
on his next steps.
</P>
<P>
Holbrooke, accompanied by State Department Special Cyprus
Coordinator Thomas Miller, will leave today for Ankara for
meetings with Turkish Prime Minister Mesut Yilmaz, Deputy Prime
Minister Bulent Ecevit, Foreign Minister Ismail Cem and other
government officials.
</P>
<P>
This is Holbrooke's first visit to the island since his
appointment by Clinton as special envoy last June.
</P>
<P>
Diplomatic sources here speculated that the purpose of
Holbrooke's visit is to persuade the two Cypriot sides to make
compromise in forming a joint delegation for the European Union
accession negotiation with Cyprus, which will start next spring.
</P>
<P>
Holbrooke was also trying to reduce tension on the
island triggered by the Cypriot government's decision to
purchase Russian-made S-300 surface-to-air missiles.
</P>
<P>
Cyprus has been divided into Greek Cypriot south and Turkish
Cypriot north since 1974 when Turkey sent troops and took over
the northern third of the island following a failed Athen-backed
coup. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19971112.0032 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-11-12 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> ECOMOG, S. Leone Junta Meet on Peace Talks </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LAGOS, November 11 (Xinhua) -- Peace talks between Sierra
Leone's military junta and the commander of the west African
peace-keeping force (ECOMOG) began today as scheduled in Kosuh,
Freetown, on details of how to restore civilian rule.
</P>
<P>
The focus of the talks will be on how the military hands over
power to President Ahmed Tejan Kabbah who was ousted in the May
25 coup this year, said Col. Godwin Ugbo, spokesman for Nigeria's
defense headquarters.
</P>
<P>
The leader of the junta, Major Johnny Paul Koroma, will also
discuss with ECOMOG Force Commander Major-General Victor Malu on
modalities to implement the peace accord signed in Conakry,
Guinea last month.
</P>
<P>
Under the agreement, the junta is to step down in April next
year.
</P>
<P>
On top of the agenda will also be such issues as a cease fire
between ECOMOG and the junta forces, the economic sanctions
imposed by west African countries and the United Nations, and the
settlement of returned refugees, Ugbo said here today.
</P>
<P>
According to him, the situation in Freetown is conducive for
the talks because "there has been no exchange of fire since the
accord".
</P>
<P>
Another major issue at the negotiation table is the
disarmament of combatants in Sierra Leone, who include the
Kamajors, the Revolutionary United Front (RUF) and the armed
forces of Sierra Leone, the spokesman said.
</P>
<P>
The Kamajors are a group of traditional hunters who fight for
President Kabbah, while RUF is a rebel group which has fought
successive governments of the country since 1991.
</P>
<P>
About 6,000 RUF fighters reportedly joined the Sierra Leonean
army shortly after the coup.
</P>
<P>
Koroma has said earlier that the ECOMOG could not disarm the
armed forces of Sierra Leone because it is the legitimate army of
the country.
</P>
<P>
This is expected to be one of the crucial issue during the
talks.
</P>
<P>
Koroma has also called for the release of Foday Sankoh, the
RUF leader who has been under house arrest in Nigeria since March
this year.
</P>
<P>
According to Ugbo, Sankoh could be released but it depends on
the outcome of the negotiation. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19971112.0033 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-11-12 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Moi Urges Concession Between Sudanese Warring </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NAIROBI, November 11 (Xinhua) -- Kenyan President Daniel arap
Moi today called on both Sudanese warring parties to make
concessions to find a lasting solution of their conflicts.
</P>
<P>
He noted that it was prudent that they make concessions and
abandon their intransigent stance as a way forward.
</P>
<P>
Moi made the remarks here when he met with delegations of the
Sudanese government and the Sudan People's Liberation Army (SPLA)
which have held peace talks in Nairobi since October 27.
</P>
<P>
Moi, who is the Chairman of the Committee of Heads of State
and Government dealing with southern Sudan conflict, noted that
southern Sudanese problems could not be solved through military
means.
</P>
<P>
The Kenyan President who is also the Chairman of the
Inter-Governmental Authority on Development (IGAD) pointed out
that he was totally committed to the peaceful settlement of the
Sudanese conflict.
</P>
<P>
In a communique issued after the meeting by Kenyan Foreign
Minister Kalonzo Musyoka who has chaired the peace talks, both
sides of the conflict accepted that a military solution could not
bring lasting peace and stability to Sudan.
</P>
<P>
They reaffirmed their commitment to the IGAD-brokered peace
initiatives and said that negotiations would continue under its
auspices.
</P>
<P>
Musyoka said the IGAD subcommittee decided that the peace
talks "should adjourn and resume in April 1998, to give ample
time for the two sides to consult with their respective
headquarters".
</P>
<P>
"In the intervening period special envoys will conduct shuttle
diplomacy between Khartoum and the Headquarters of the SPLA to
narrow the gap on the issues," he added.
</P>
<P>
During the closed-door talks sponsored by the IGAD, the SPLA
proposed a referendum on self-determination for south Sudan after
two years, with a confederation between north and south in the
interim period.
</P>
<P>
Khartoum accepted the principle of self-determination as a
means of resolving the 14-year conflict, but proposed a
north-south federation in stead of confederation.
</P>
<P>
The talks between the two sides stalled in 1994 when the
Sudanese government refused to accept a declaration containing
the principle of self-determination for south Sudan, but a
combination of military defeats and diplomatic pressure forced
the government back to the negotiating table last September.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
