<DATE_TIME> 1997-11-12 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> ECOMOG, Liberia Dispute over Border Deployment </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LAGOS, November 11 (Xinhua) -- There has been a new dispute
between the west African peace-keeping force (ECOMOG) and the
Liberian government over the deployment of security forces along
the Liberian-Sierra Leone border.
</P>
<P>
The two sides have disputed over the restructuring of the
Liberian armed forces as the Liberian government plans to do the
job by itself.
</P>
<P>
Speaking with delegates from the European Union last night in
Monrovia, capital of Liberia, ECOMOG Force Commander
Major-General Victor Malu rejected the Liberian government's plan
to deploy armed Liberians to the country's western border.
</P>
<P>
ECOMOG is mandated by west African leaders to take
responsibility of Liberia's security after the newly-elected
government was put in place.
</P>
<P>
Malu said that to avoid clashes he will be compelled to
withdraw his force from the border if the Liberian government
insists on deploying armed elements there.
</P>
<P>
"I have no intention of allowing clashes to break up there
during my tenure," Malu said, quoted by the British Broadcasting
Corporation today.
</P>
<P>
He said with the presence of ECOMOG and Liberia's armed
elements in one place, it resulted in fighting in Monrovia more
than a year ago.
</P>
<P>
Malu pointed out that since last June's heavy concentration of
ECOMOG troops along the Liberia-Sierra Leone border, there has
never been any threat to Liberia's security.
</P>
<P>
He said he was not aware of the sources of all the arms the
government has been issuing to Liberian security forces, adding
that it appeared imaginary insecurity at the border is being used
as an excuse to give weapons to the people the government wants
to re-arm.
</P>
<P>
Malu firmly denounced this re-armament, saying that it was
being done in disregard to the peace agreement that has brought
peace to the country.
</P>
<P>
According to the agreement signed in August last year in
Abuja, capital of Nigeria, ECOMOG will be involved in the
restructuring and training of the Liberian armed forces.
</P>
<P>
Liberian President Charles Taylor announced last month his
government would single-handedly re-organize an armed force of
1,000.
</P>
<P>
Taylor's Defense Minister Daniel Chea also said the Abuja
peace agreement which calls the ECOMOG involvement in the
formation of the new Liberian army had ceased to exist with the
coming into power of the Charles Taylor-led government. 
</P>
</TEXT>
