<HEADLINE> Russian Official Praises Results of Yeltsin's China Visit </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MOSCOW, November 11 (Xinhua) -- President Boris Yeltsin's China
visit proved that Russian-Chinese ties "are stably developing in
the channel of equal partnership based on mutual confidence and
aimed at strategic interaction in the 21st century," Russian
Foreign Ministry spokesman Gennady Tarasov said today.
</P>
<P>
Tarasov said at a press briefing that during the visit, the
Russian and Chinese presidents exchanged views on bilateral
relations and international problems and signed a joint statement.
</P>
<P>
The two sides settled all essential issues related to
demarcation of the Russian-Chinese state border in its eastern
part (over 4,200 kilometers) done in accordance with the agreement
of May 16, 1991, and confirmed their readiness to do the
demarcation work in the western part of the Russian-Chinese border
(55 kilometers) in coordinated time.
</P>
<P>
According to the spokesman, the two leaders expressed
satisfaction with the mounting positive dynamics in relations
between Russia, China, the United States and Japan achieved during
recent summit contacts.
</P>
<P>
The two leaders agreed to and called for a multipolar world and
said the time of unions aimed against third countries as well as
strategic "polygons" has gone.
</P>
<P>
Tarasov also said that the two sides paid much attention to
boosting of trade and economic cooperation. They noted the need
for a fuller use of their potential in such spheres as oil, gas,
nuclear power engineering, transport, communication and peaceful
use of outer space.
</P>
<P>
The visit resulted in signing of eight bilateral documents.
</P>
<P>
The Russian president visited China on November 9-11. It was
the third time for Yeltsin to visit Beijing since he was elected
Russian president, and was also his fifth meeting with Chinese
leaders.
</P>
<P>
The Russian and Chinese leaders reached an agreement to hold
their next summit in an informal atmosphere in Russia, Tarasov
said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
