<HEADLINE> Zambia Reiterates Support to Angola's Peace </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LUSAKA, November 11 (Xinhua) -- Zambia today reiterated its
support to the promotion of Angola's peace and stability,
according to a television report by Zambia News Broadcasting
Corporation Limited (ZNBC).
</P>
<P>
Officiating at the Angolan 22nd independence anniversary in
the capital today, David Mpamba, minister of information and
broadcasting services, said that Zambia will continue to support
all the political processes to bring about peace and stability in
Angola in accordance with the 1994 Lusaka peace protocol for that
country.
</P>
<P>
Mpamba said that it is only through conditions of peace and
stability that people can devote their time, energies and
resources that could address social, economic and political
challenges.
</P>
<P>
People of Angola, said the minister, like all the people in
the sub-region and Africa as a whole, "deserve unconditional
peace and stability to forge ahead in bringing economic and
political dispensation."
</P>
<P>
He added that all the African countries need peace to go ahead
in order to win economic independence in the region.
</P>
<P>
On the same occasion, Manuel Augusto, Angolan ambassador to
Zambia, called for the support of the international community to
ensure that the Lusaka agreement is realized in full.
</P>
<P>
He said with such support, the agreement will be fully
implemented to enable Angola to pursue developmental activities
successfully.
</P>
<P>
On November 20, 1994, the Angolan government and the
anti-government organization UNITA signed a ceasefire agreement
in Lusaka in a bid to make peace in Angola which has suffered a
civil war since mid-1970s.
</P>
<P>
However, the agreement has not been implemented smoothly and
periodic fightings between the two sides continue. 
</P>
