<HEADLINE> 613 Cataract Patients Regain Sight in Ethiopia </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ADDIS ABABA, November 11 (Xinhua) -- President of the Lions
Club Ethiopia Tebebe Yemane-Birehan said today that 613 cataract
patients in Addis Ababa and Wolayita, south Ethiopia regained
their sight as a result of two eye camps the club carried out in
the areas.
</P>
<P>
Speaking at a press conference here, the president indicated
that in the first eye camp that took place in Addis Ababa from
October 4 to 12, some 173 cataract patients were operated.
</P>
<P>
Similarly, he said, during the second eye camp conducted in
Wolayita-Sodo from October 24 to November 2, 440 cataract
patients had been operated.
</P>
<P>
Tebebe further noted that in the Walayita-Sodo Eye Camp, over
2,500 eye patients were screened, out of whom some 80 percent
were found to be trichiasis sufferers.
</P>
<P>
"The majority of the patients were in the age group of 20 to
35 years old," he said, adding that through the two eye camps the
Lions Club was able to restore sight to the reported number of
cataract patients who had been suffering from blindness from 6 to
20 years.
</P>
<P>
There are about 800,000 cataract patients in Ethiopia,
according to Tebebe. 
</P>
</TEXT>
