<DATE_TIME> 1997-11-11 18:39 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Israeli Former Security Head Warns About Political </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JERUSALEM, November 11 (Xinhua) -- A former Israeli security
head warned today that another political assassination is
possible because of the deepening division among Israeli society
two years after the killing of late prime minister Yitzhak Rabin.
</P>
<P>
Yaakov Peri, former head of General Security Service (GSS),
sounded the alarm in his report to the Knesset (Parliament)
Foreign Affairs and Defense Committee. He said threats come from
both the left and right wings, and the GSS has to cope with them
seriously to prevent another tragedy.
</P>
<P>
Asked if another political murder is possible in light of the
current tense political atmosphere, Peri replied: "Yes, because
of the environment, because of the debate which we're
having... we have to do our utmost in order to prevent it," he
told Israel Radio.
</P>
<P>
Peri's grim assessment of the situation coincided with the
second anniversary of the assassination of Yitzhak Rabin that
began this evening according to the Jewish calendar.
</P>
<P>
Rabin was shot dead by a radical Jew named Yigal Amir on
November 4, 1995, at a political rally in Tel Aviv. The leftists
have been blaming Rabin's murder on the rightist camp led by
current Prime Minister Benjamin Netanyahu.
</P>
<P>
Leading opposition leaders are demanding for an official
apology from Netanyahu for his role in fanning the incitement
that led to Rabin's assassination.
</P>
<P>
At the biggest ever political rally held last Saturday in Tel
Aviv's Rabin Square where Rabin was killed, 200,000 leftists
gathered to remember Rabin and attacked Netanyahu for his
refusal to apologize. Some posted placards saying "We'll not
forget, We'll not forgive."
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, a public debate between the left and right on a
conspiracy theory surrounding Rabin's death reached a feverish
peak in recent days, as the two sides sparred over the role
played by former GSS agent Avishai Raviv in inciting Amir to
kill Rabin.
</P>
<P>
The government has decided to publish Wednesday some
secret sections of the report compiled by the committee
appointed to probe Rabin's assassination two years ago.
</P>
<P>
Raviv, a problematic agent who infiltrated extreme rightist
groups and was a close friend of Amir, was charged by the
rightist camp for organizing the incitement campaign against
Rabin. Some ministers within the current right-wing government
have called for conducting new investigation into Raviv's role
and bringing him to trial.
</P>
<P>
However, the left wing denounced the right wing for plotting
to shift its responsibility for Rabin's death by placing the
blame on the back of Raviv.
</P>
<P>
Peri, who retired before Rabin's killing, defended the GSS in
employing such controversial figure like Raviv. He criticized
the right wing's exaggeration of Raviv's role in Rabin's murder,
saying no one should put all the blame on Raviv because his
provocative actions were approved by the GSS in a cautious
manner.
</P>
<P>
Senior police commander Avi Cohen agreed with Peri's
assessment that another political assassination in Israel is
possible because of the current tension. He said although there
are no outright signs now, "the smell of another political
assassination is in the air."
</P>
<P>
In the first sign pointing to the security warnings, Benny
Elon, leader of the ultra-rightist Moledet party, received a
death threat today contained in an envelope addressed to him
with a bullet inside. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
