<HEADLINE> Iran Concerned About Tension in Northern Iraq </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
TEHRAN, November 11 (Xinhua) -- Iran today expressed concern
over the rising factional conflicts and the Turkish incursion in
northern Iraq, the official news agency IRNA reported.
</P>
<P>
Iran is against the rising tensions in northern Iraq as well as
the expansion of the Turkish army's operations in the war-torn
region, Iranian Foreign Ministry spokesman Mahmoud Mohammadi was
quoted by the agency as saying.
</P>
<P>
Mohammadi, who is currently accompanying Iranian Foreign
Minister Kamal Kharrazi for a visit to the Gulf region, noted that
the Turkish military intervention in the conflicts between the two
Kurdish rival factions in northern Iraq would further complicate
the already complex situation.
</P>
<P>
This would lead to destruction and bloodshed in the region and
force civilians to seek refuge inside the Iranian territory, he
said, warning that Iran has insufficient resources to host more
refugees in the upcoming winter season.
</P>
<P>
He urged the Turkish army to refrain from interfering in the
conflicts between the two Iraqi Kurdish groups, adding that Turkey
should pull back its forces from the Iraqi territory.
</P>
<P>
Fresh fightings erupted in the past few days between the
pro-Iranian Patriotic Union of Kurdistan (PUK) and pro-Baghdad
Kurdistan's Democratic Party (KDP), forcing many Kurdish people to
flee from the region bordering Iran.
</P>
<P>
More than 60,000 Iraqi Kurds fled into the Iranian territory
in September last year when the KDP forces pushed the PUK to the
Iranian border areas.
</P>
<P>
Several thousands of the Iraqi Kurdish people are still
living in Iran's refugee camps. It is believed that more Iraqi
Kurdish refugees would enter Iran if the factional fighting
continues. 
</P>
</TEXT>
