<HEADLINE> Iran Blames Azerbaijan for Exploitation in </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
TEHRAN, November 11 (Xinhua) -- Iran today blamed Azerbaijan
for its "unilateral exploitation" in the Caspian Sea, saying that
the unilateral measure would bring chaos and discord to the
region.
</P>
<P>
The Iranian official news agency IRNA quoted a Foreign
Ministry official for legal affairs as saying that Azerbaijan's
measure would trigger an adverse repercussion in other littoral
states of the Caspian Sea.
</P>
<P>
It is reported that Azerbaijan would formally inaugurate its
oil exploration operation at Cheragh area in the Caspian Sea
Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
The official said the resources of the Caspian Sea belong to
all the littoral states and any extraction of the resources and
the utility of its facilities needed to be approached through
international conventions and a legal approach unanimously
approved by the Caspian Sea littoral states.
</P>
<P>
Any unilateral action to be taken by Azerbaijan in exploiting
the resources of the Caspian Sea is in contradiction with the
"1921 Amity Convention" and the "Commercial and Sea-faring
Convention of 1940" signed by Iran and former Soviet Union,
he stressed.
</P>
<P>
He noted that Azerbaijan, as one of the newly independent
republics of former Soviet Union, has legally bound itself to the
commitments of former Soviet Union by signing the "1991 Almaty
Declaration."
</P>
<P>
The Caspian Sea is reported to have proven reserves of 16
billion barrels of crude oil and 8.3 trillion barrels of natural
gas.
</P>
<P>
During the past years, Azerbaijan signed several contracts
with foreign companies to form a consortium to conduct oil
exploration and exploitation in the Caspian Sea, arousing sharp
criticism from other Caspian Sea states such as Iran.
</P>
<P>
Tehran stressed that a legal regime governing the Caspian Sea
should be reached unanimously by the five littoral states,
including Iran, Azerbaijan, Russia, Kazakhstan and
Turkmenistan. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
