<DOCNO> XIE19971112.0049 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-11-12 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Canada Has More Millionaires </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
OTTAWA, November 11 (Xinhua) -- The number of millionaires has
tripled in Canada since 1989, said a report today.
</P>
<P>
At present, the country has 220,000 people with investable
assets valued at more than 1 million dollars (710,000 US dollars),
1 percent of Canadian taxpayers.
</P>
<P>
And the number of Canadian millionaires is expected to triple
again by 2005, the Globe and Mail newspaper reported.
</P>
<P>
The investable assets are defined as savings or investments
that are liquid and controlled by the individual. This includes
items such as stocks and saving bonds, but does not include equity
in a house or a company pension plan.
</P>
<P>
More than half of Canadian millionaires earned their money
through inheritance or selling a business or property as opposed
to playing the stock market.
</P>
<P>
Yet, the percentage of millionaires who grew wealthy from the
stock market is expected to increase over the next decade.
</P>
<P>
In addition, as the baby boom generation ages, membership in
the million-dollar club will increase as boomers step up their
savings efforts and come into inheritance, the report said.
</P>
<P>
There are a number of Canadians currently sitting on
500,000-plus that they made playing the stock market and many of
these people will hit the 1-million-dollar mark soon, it added.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
