<DOCNO> XIE19971112.0050 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-11-11 19:46 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> News Analysis: Egypt Asserts Independence on Doha </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CAIRO, November 11 (Xinhua) -- Egypt today declared its
non-participation at a controversial economic conference in a move
to underscore its independence as against the favor of the United
States.
</P>
<P>
After months of waiting and seeing, President Hosni Mubarak
said today that Egypt will not send any delegation to the fourth
Middle East and North Africa (MENA) Economic Conference and, at
the best, its ambassador to Doha might attend the inaugural
ceremony.
</P>
<P>
"Every state adopts its own decision based on its own
assessment and its sovereignty," Mubarak said. And Egypt's
decision took into consideration the benefits to be gained through
holding the conference either by the state or the whole Arab
nation, he said.
</P>
<P>
By doing so, Egypt not merely sent a protest note to Washington
for its biased policy toward Israel, but also retained the dignity
of the Arab nations outraged by the hardline Israeli government,
observers said.
</P>
<P>
The U.S., though apparently failed to pressure Israel into
implementing unfulfilled peace agreements and stopping
controversial settlement activities, has pushed Egypt hard to show
up at the annual gathering.
</P>
<P>
The first tour of U.S. Secretary of State Madeleine Albright to
the region in September, expected to breathe new life to the peace
process, only turned out to be a selling pitch for Doha.
</P>
<P>
However, disheartened by the peace crisis going into the eighth
month, Egypt said its participation would hinge on progress on the
peace process and it cannot make a decision against the will of
the Arab people, even if at the risk of losing U.S. favor.
</P>
<P>
When most Arab states have either flatly rejected the
conference or threatened to boycott it, Egypt decided to wait for
any breakthrough while consulting Arab brothers. Of the 16 Arab
countries invited, only four promised to come.
</P>
<P>
In the past few days, Egypt concerted steps with leaders of the
United Arab Emirates, Bahrain, Saudi Arabia and Oman, held talks
with Russian, Canadian and European diplomats, exchanged views
with the U.S. undersecretary. Egyptian Ambassador to Qatar was
recalled for consultations.
</P>
<P>
And finally it was told today by the Palestinian negotiating
team in Cairo that the Washington-backed talks with Israel was
futile.
</P>
<P>
No Egyptian delegation or businessmen will show up at Doha. But
to maintain "a minimum level of contacts" with the host Qatar,
Cairo said it will send back the ambassador this week and he might
go to the inaugural ceremony.
</P>
<P>
Egypt, however frustrated with the peace process, asserts its
role as an Arab leader, an honor so far largely limited to hosting
pan-Arab meetings and issuing appeals, observers said.
</P>
<P>
As the Arab camp is divided over the MENA conference, the
belated Egyptian decision is expected to discourage those still
hesitant to go to Doha.
</P>
<P>
It also gave a relief to those who had in private complained
that Egypt cannot do without the U.S. guidance in view of
Washington's annual 2-billion-dollar assistance to Egypt. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
