<DOCNO> XIE19971112.0051 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-11-12 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> ECOMOG, S. Leone Junta to Continue Talks Tomorrow </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LAGOS, November 11 (Xinhua) -- The west African peacekeeping
force (ECOMOG) and Sierra Leone's military junta have decided to
continue their peace talks tomorrow at the end of today's meeting
which was held in a "good atmosphere".
</P>
<P>
Today's meeting, which had to be postponed from last Friday
because of disagreement on the venue, was attended by the ECOMOG
team headed by Force Commander Major-General Victor Malu and the
juta's group led Major Johnny Paul Koroma, the self-named head of
state, in Jui near the capital Freetown.
</P>
<P>
The two sides discussed, among the 17 items on the agenda, the
responsibility of ECOMOG in Sierra Leone, the British
Broadcasting Corporation reported today.
</P>
<P>
Other issues being discussed include the deployment of troops
in Freetown port, manning of checkpoints, arms control in
Freetown, free movement of civil servants, including personnel of
humanitarian services and non-governmental organization as well
as refugees and displaced persons.
</P>
<P>
They also talked about the deployment to enforce the embargo
imposed by west African countries and the United Nations, the
removal of land mines, opening of air and sea ports, UN
involvement and opening of borders.
</P>
<P>
According to Malu, he had actually given instructions to
ECOMOG troops in Sierra Leone to cooperate with soldiers of the
ruling Armed Forces Revolutionary Council (AFRC).
</P>
<P>
The two parties agreed to the release of Foday Sankoh, leader
of the rebel Revolutionary United Front (RUF), who has been
detained in Nigeria since March this year, and the disarmament of
combatants in the country.
</P>
<P>
About 6,000 RUF fighters reportedly joined the AFRC army after
the May 25 coup that ousted Sierra Leone's legitimate government
led by President Ahmed Tejan Kabbah.
</P>
<P>
They agreed that the Sierra Leone army and ECOMOG troops would
be deployed at strategic positions across Sierra Leone, as well
as mining areas and places of commercial or economic interest of
the country.
</P>
<P>
They also agreed that the removal of mines should be started
immediately as well as the manning of checkpoints, while all arms
and combatants should be moved out of the city until the start of
the disarmament.
</P>
<P>
Malu was quoted as saying that the atmosphere of the meeting
was very good for confidence building.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
