<HEADLINE> First Israeli Flights Land at Jordan's Aqaba </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
AMMAN, November 11 (Xinhua) -- The first two Israeli planes
landed today at the airport of Aqaba, Jordan's Red Sea resort,
under an agreement signed between the two countries last August.
</P>
<P>
An El Al plane with 189 passengers on board flew from St.
Petersburg, Russia and the other from Frankfurt, Germany, Jordan's
official news agency Petra reported.
</P>
<P>
About 60 passengers, mostly Israelis, were driven in bus to
Israel's Eilat through the Wadi Araba crossing.
</P>
<P>
According to the aviation agreement, flights heading for
Israel's Eilat may land at the Aqaba Airport in a period of four
months to ease the crowdedness of the Eilat Airport.
</P>
<P>
The two countries are also seeking to establish a joint airport
to serve the twin Red Sea resorts of Eilat and Aqaba.
</P>
<P>
The future airport is named "Aqaba-Eilat Peace Airport" and
aimed to promote tourism.
</P>
<P>
Jordan signed a peace treaty with Israel in 1994 and is one of
the only two Arab countries after Egypt to set up diplomatic
relationship with the Jewish state. 
</P>
</TEXT>
