<BODY>
<HEADLINE> IMF Approves Three-Year Loan for Uganda </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, November 11 (Xinhua) -- The International Monetary
Fund (IMF) today announced the approval of a three-year loan for
Uganda under the Enhanced Structural Adjustment Facility (ESAF),
in an amount of equivalent to 138 million U.S. dollars.
</P>
<P>
The loan is provided in support of the Ugandan government's
economic program for 1997/98 to 1999/2000. The first annual loan,
in an amount of about 55 million dollars, is made available in two
equal semiannual installments, and the first of which is available
immediately.
</P>
<P>
The principal objectives of the economic program, supported by
the ESAF loans, are to sustain high and broad-based economic
growth and ensure that the poor are able to participate in, and
benefit from, increased economic activity. The program is aimed to
achieve a real GDP growth rate of at least 7 percent a year on
average, reducing annual inflation to about 5 percent and
increasing gross international reserves to the equivalent of 4.9
months of imports of goods and nonfactor services.
</P>
<P>
At the core of the government's medium-term program is an
increase in the gross investment-to-GDP ratio to about 23 percent
in 1999/2000, and a reduction in the overall fiscal deficit by
about 1.7 percent of GDP over the program period.
</P>
<P>
The ESAF is a concessional IMF facility for assisting the
member countries that are undertaking economic reform programs to
strengthen their balance of payments and improve their growth
prospects. The loans carry an interest rate of 0.5 percent a year
and are repayable over 10 years with a 5.5 year grace period.
</P>
<P>
Uganda joined the IMF in September 1963. Its quota is about 185
million dollars and its outstanding use of IMF financing currently
totals about 380 million dollars. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19971112.0061 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-11-12 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Cohen: No Delay for Resolving Iraqi Defiance </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, November 11 (Xinhua) -- The United States is afraid
that "endless delay" for settlement of dispute over Iraq's
preventing U.N. arms inspection teams including Americans from
discharging their job could give its mortal foe time to rebuild
banned weapons program.
</P>
<P>
Defense Secretary William Cohen told CNN in an interview on
Tuesday morning that "time is of the essence" for the United
Nations to pressure Iraq to comply with U.N. arms inspection
resolutions.
</P>
<P>
"Iraq would not be able to reconstitute a serious weapons
program in a matter of days," Cohen said. But "if the delay were
to carry on for months then that would be a different situation."
</P>
<P>
"That's why time really is of the essence here... the longer
this goes on the longer he (Iraqi President Saddam Hussein) has an
opportunity to continue to build the kind of weapons that really
are banned and he should be precluded from doing so," he
emphasized.
</P>
<P>
Iraq has barred U.N. weapons inspection teams for more than a
week, claiming it did so because Americans were included in the
the teams and they were collecting sensitive informations under
the guise of weapons inspections.
</P>
<P>
The United States has repeatedly urged the United Nations to
take punitive measures as soon as possible on Iraq so that it
could be further restricted for its revival in its weapons
programs.
</P>
<P>
Cohen said Baghdad's continued defiance amounted to an
"endless delay," and any attempt on Iraq's part to seek dialogue
should be rejected as it gives the chance for such a delay.
</P>
<P>
"Endless delay, or his attempt to engage in dialogue, should
be rejected. This is not a dialogue, it's not a debate," he said.
</P>
<P>
When asked whether the United States would take military action
against Iraq by moving warships and planes into the Persian Gulf
areas, Cohen said the Pentagon was considering several options
in dealing with Saddam Hussein's defiance towards the United States.
</P>
<P>
"We would be prepared, should it be necessary, to use
whatever resources we have available in order to bring about a
resolution of this," he said.
</P>
<P>
Cohen and Henry Shelton, chairman of the Joint Chiefs of
Staff, has postponed a 12-day trip to Asia so that he could be
directly involved in decision making on Iraq.
</P>
<P>
"I postponed the trip at the request of President (Bill)
Clinton, who wanted his national security team to be available
to consult with should any sort of military action be necessary
in the future," he said.
</P>
<P>
Cohen, however, said Washington first seeks diplomatic
solution before taking into consideration any possibility of
military action.
</P>
<P>
"We're seeking a diplomatic solution not a military solution
but obviously we would call upon a variety of our assets to carry
out a demand or a command on the part of the president of the
United States and in conjunction with the U.N. to carry out the
situation," he said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
