<HEADLINE> EU to Cope With Defense Industry Problems </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>

<P>
BRUSSELS, November 12 (Xinhua) -- The European Union (EU)
today adopted a strategy to deal with problems facing the European
defense industry.
</P>
<P>
Noting that the European defense-related industry is too
fragmented to be sustainable, the EU's executive agency, the
European Commission, adopted a strategy which is aimed at
effectively restructuring the industry.
</P>
<P>
The EU holds that a sharp decline in demand following the end of
the Cold War, as well as fierce competition from newly created
"giant" corporations in the United States, has put the future of
EU's defense industry at stake.
</P>
<P>
The strategy, initiated by EU Commissioners Martin
Bangemann and Hans Van den Broek, will list the problems emerging
in Europe's defense industry, which represents a gross turnover of
50 billion US dollars inside the EU, and employs some
700,000 people directly in member countries.
</P>
<P>
For the implementation of the strategy, the Commission also
recommended a dual approach: development of a European armaments
policy and an action plan for defense-related industries.
</P>
<P>
Defense-related industry is not only economically vital to the
EU's employment but also highly sensitive in political and
security fields, the commission said in a press release issued
here Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
According to the International Institute for Strategic
Studies, the EU imports six times more defense-related goods from
the U.S. than it exports to the U.S., and the figure is
increasing. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
