<HEADLINE> EU Adopts Plan for Free movement of Workers </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>

<P>
BRUSSELS, November 12 (Xinhua) -- The European Commission, the
European Union (EU)'s executive body, today set out a comprehensive
action plan to improve the conditions for the free movement of
workers within the EU.
</P>
<P>
The EU needed to "take decisive action" to deal with the
problem though the main European rules on free movement of workers
were adopted almost 20 years ago, Padraig Flynn, EU commissioner for
employment and social affairs, said Wednesday in Brussels.
</P>
<P>
The action plan will focus on areas such as improving existing
legislation, making the European labor market more transparent,
enhancing cooperation with and between national authorities and
social partners and giving greater visibility to the right of free
movement.
</P>
<P>
The Commission's strategy builds on the recommendations made
last March by a high-level panel on free movement of people, which
highlights the importance of labor mobility in the proper
functioning of the envisaged Single Market and in the promotion of a
skilled, trained and adaptable workforce.
</P>
</TEXT>
