<HEADLINE> Swiss President Leaves Nepal For Vietnam </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
KATHMANDU, November 12 (Xinhua) -- President of the Swiss
Confederation Arnold Koller left here today for Vietnam, after
concluding a four-day official visit to Nepal.
</P>
<P>
During his stay in Nepal, Koller held official talks with
Nepali Prime Minister Surya Bahadur Thapa. Koller said the Swiss
government would like to play the role of mediator to help resolve
the long-standing issue of Bhutanese refugees.
</P>
<P>
About 100,000 Bhutanese refugees have been staying in eastern
Nepal after being forced to flee Bhutan in 1989 and the early
1990s.
</P>
<P>
Nepal had asked India to help resolve the issue, but India
refused, saying it is a bilateral one.
</P>
<P>
Koller also said the Swiss government plans to provide yearly
assistance of some 20 million Swiss francs (14.93 million U.S.
dollars) in a five-year period starting 1997.
</P>
<P>
During his visit, the first ever by a Swiss head of state, the
two sides signed two agreements under which Switzerland will grant
some 3.41 million dollars to Nepal for building suspension
bridges.
</P>
<P>
Switzerland provides aid to Nepal mainly in transport,
vocational training and rural development.
</P>
<P>
After Vietnam, the Swiss president will visit Thailand.
</P>
</TEXT>
