<HEADLINE> Indonesia's Inflation Rises to 7.36 Percent </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JAKARTA, November 12 (Xinhua) -- Indonesia's inflation rate
rose by 2.01 percent during the January-October period of this
year and it also hit a 10-year high last month, Information
Minister Hartono said today.
</P>
<P>
Indonesia's inflation stood at 7.36 percent during
January-October, compared with 5.35 percent recorded in the same
period of last year, Hartono said after attending a monthly
cabinet meeting.
</P>
<P>
October's inflation rate was 1.99 percent, the highest in 10
years, he said.
</P>
<P>
"The Agriculture Ministry, the Industry and Trade Ministry and
the National Logistics Board were asked (by President Soeharto) to
take measures to control the inflation by adjusting demands to
supplies," Hartono said.
</P>
<P>
The foreign exchange reserves held by the government totaled
19.08 billion U.S. dollars and reserved stand-by loans were about
two billion dollars, he said.
</P>
<P>
According to Hartono, the country's foreign exchange reserves
were enough to finance imports for five months. 
</P>
