<HEADLINE> UAE Reaffirms Boycott of Doha Conference </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ABU DHABI, November 12 (Xinhua) -- The United Arab Emirates
(UAE) today reaffirmed its decision to boycott the fourth Middle
East and North Africa (MENA) economic conference, the WAM News
Agency reported.
</P>
<P>
A statement issued to the agency by the Foreign Ministry said
that the Gulf country will "never take part in the Doha
conference."
</P>
<P>
The MENA conference is scheduled to open in the Qatari capital
Doha on Sunday. The former three were convened in Morocco, Jordan
and Egypt.
</P>
<P>
The conference, originally intended to promote regional
economic integration, has divided the Arab world due to the
participation of Israel.
</P>
<P>
A number of Arab countries like Egypt, Syria, Lebanon and Saudi
Arabia have also announced to stay away from the conference in
protest against the deadlock of the Arab-Israeli talks caused by
Israel's hardline policy in the Middle East peace process.
</P>
<P>
Only Yemen, Jordan, Oman and Kuwait from the Arab world have
announced to attend the conference. 
</P>
