<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Accords Reached to Bring S. Leone Back to Normal </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
FREETOWN, November 12 (Xinhua) -- Commander of the West
African Peace Keeping Force (ECOMOG) Victor Malu and military
officials in the Sierra Leone Army reached a number of agreements
Tuesday after day-long talks.
</P>
<P>
In an interview with Xinhua at the end of the meeting, Malu
said, "we are well on our way to bringing Sierra Leone back to
normal after the May 25 coup."
</P>
<P>
He said the country's ferry service, which links the mainland
with the international airport will resume soon and that ECOMOG
troops "will shortly be deployed in specific areas to enforce the
embargo in such a way that will not bring hardship to the people
of Sierra Leone."
</P>
<P>
The land mines at the airport, he said, will be removed and
humanitarian food supplies will be allowed into the country as
from Friday.
</P>
<P>
"There is a lot of food now at the border with Guinea and the
agencies are waiting for the green light from us to come in," he
said.
</P>
<P>
On the list of discussions at the talks, he said, "the sea and
airports are to be re-opened soon and Sierra Leone prisoners of
war are to be released to the International Committee of the Red
Cross and the Catholic mission as from tomorrow (Wednesday)."
</P>
<P>
"There are however three key issues that require further
discussions by the Committee of Five" of the Economic Community
of West African States (ECOWAS), said Malu.
</P>
<P>
ECOWAS assigned Nigeria, Ghana, Guinea, Cote d'Ivoire and
Liberia as the Committee of Five to hold talks with Sierra Leone
junta for handing over power back to elected President T. Kabbah.
The junta toppled Kabbah's government in a May coup.
</P>
<P>
Malu listed the issues as "the return of Corporal Foray
Sankoh, an observation on who should be disarmed and the dominant
role of Nigeria in ECOMOG."
</P>
<P>
"We have asked the military government in Sierra Leone to
immediately start reopening the roads and dismantle unnecessary
checkpoints which will later be manned by a joint Sierra Leone
army and ECOMOG soldiers," he noted.
</P>
<P>
Malu said that three committees on disarmament, cease fire and
humanitarian agencies would be set up within 48 hours.
</P>
<P>
"We have agreed on ECOMOG deployment in Freetown which
includes the seaports, airports and other selected vulnerable
points and strategic installations including guarding the
facilities of the U.N. agencies and non-governmental
organizations in conjunction with the Sierra Leone army," he
said.
</P>
<P>
A spokesman with the Sierra Leone military delegation said
they have accepted the agreement "in principle" and that "further
discussions were necessary to put them into gear."
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, residents in the capital welcomed the agreement,
with many calling it "a forward move for peace and security" in
Sierra Leone. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19971112.0080 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-11-12 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Trial Journey of Sped Up Train Successful </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HANGZHOU, November 12 (Xinhua) -- China has been successful in
a trial journey of a high-speed train.
</P>
<P>
A high-speed train left Shanghai at 9:45 a.m. today on a maiden
voyage and arrived in Hangzhou at 11:41 a.m. It headed for Ningbo
after a 45-minute stop and arrived there at 3:03 p.m.
</P>
<P>
The train cut 50 minutes off the previous time by running at
120 kilometers per hour from Shanghai to Hangzhou, and 110
kilometers per hour from Hangzhou to Ningbo.
</P>
<P>
This was the second run of a high-speed train. The first, from
Shanghai to Nanjing, started on April 1, 1996.
</P>
<P>
The high-speed trains are expected to take business away from
the Hangzhou-Ningbo expressway, which opened to automobiles at the
end of last year, and the Shanghai-Hangzhou expressway, which is
expected to be operational in the second half of next year.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19971112.0081 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-11-12 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Mercedes Urges to End Debate over A-Class Car's Safety </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BONN, November 12 (Xinhua) -- Daimler-Benz, maker of the new
small Mercedes A-Class car, made full-page advertizements in 180
German papers today in an unprecedented move to calm down debate
over the safety of the car, which turned over during a test in
Sweden last month.
</P>
<P>
It said in the advertisement: "We want to end the discussion
about the safety of the A-Class, once and for all."
</P>
<P>
The company said that it regretted that tests had highlighted a
weakness of the subcompact car and that it wanted to gain
confidence of the customers.
</P>
<P>
In Sweden last month, the Mercedes A-Class car rolled over when
taking a sharp turn to avoid obstacles during the test known as
the "elk test", which is designed to see how a car reacts when
avoiding suddenly-appeared obstacles.
</P>
<P>
"Please give us time and exercise some patience even if you
think the measures are somewhat excessive", said Daimler-Benz in
the advertizement.
</P>
<P>
The parent company of carmaker Mercedes-Benz Tuesday announced
that it was halting the delivery of the new A-Class car for 12
weeks for modifications of the model.
</P>
<P>
It said that all future A-Class cars would have different tyres
and an electronic suspension regulation system called ESP.
</P>
<P>
The modifications would also be applied to the 3,000 sold
models free of charge.
</P>
<P>
Daimler-Benz said that it had written to 200,000 customers and
potential buyers of the A-Class to explain the measures.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
