<DATE_TIME> 1997-11-12 13:45 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> News Analysis: Doha Conference, A Tale of Two </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CAIRO, November 12 (Xinhua) -- To be or not to be at the Doha
regional economic conference has been the question grinding Arab
countries for months. But on the eve of the opening, many came out
to say no.
</P>
<P>
Yet, behind the question is the fact that the stalled
Middle East peace process is seriously threatening the fate of
the three-year-old Middle East and North Africa (MENA) economic
cooperation process marked by annual conferences.
</P>
<P>
The MENA Doha conference, the fourth in a series, is facing
the strongest ever boycott camp which comprises of about half of
the Arab countries led by regional powers Egypt and Saudi Arabia.
</P>
<P>
Arabs regard the gathering, which includes Israelis, as a
reward to the Netanyahu government's hardline policy held
responsible for bogging down the Middle East peace process.
</P>
<P>
The apparently sagging atmosphere accompanying the boycott
presents a striking contrast with that at the first Casablanca
summit in 1994 which was meant for a bright Arab-Israeli economic
cooperation, observers noted.
</P>
<P>
The economic cooperation process, a spinoff of the breakthrough
in the peace process, also went well at the Amman summit in 1995,
but suffered a setback and was downgraded to a ministerial level
at the last Cairo meeting as the result of the protest against the
new Israeli Likud government's hardline policy towards peace.
</P>
<P>
The Doha conference, however, is being held in an even worse
situation as the mideast peace process has been at the lowest ebb
since initiated four years ago. Many Arab countries adopted a
wait-and-see stance and condition their attendance on any peace
progress by Israel - a chance that did not come.
</P>
<P>
The boycott came as a blow to the United States, a chief
sponsor of the two processes, for its widely-accused biased policy
in favor of the Israelis.
</P>
<P>
U.S. officials, including Secretary of State Madeleine
Albright, toured the region for the past few months to boost
the conference. They said exchanges between the Israeli economy
and those of Arabs - which are considered highly complementary
to each other - will serve as an impetus to the peace
process.
</P>
<P>
The U.S. also was the first to register its attendance in an
apparent move to counter Arabs' call for a postponement, a mass
boycott or cancellation of the meeting.
</P>
<P>
Therefore, the root of the dispute over the Doha conference is
the clash of two philosophies on the peace process: an
Arab-Israeli economic cooperation process fuels the peace process
as favored by the U.S. and Israel, and the inverse thinking by
many Arab countries.
</P>
<P>
Arab analysts said that any trade-without-peace practice will
only benefit Israel -- a country geographically beleagured and
economically blocked by its Arab neighbors -- with an open
Arab market to its long-cherished wish, while Arabs gain nothing
in return.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, it undermines the decades-long Arab collective
economic sanctions against Israel, thus depriving Arabs' of
bargaining chips in peace negotiations, they said.
</P>
<P>
Furthermore, reasons for boycott are backed by economic
considerations. Firstly, Arabs have shown more enthusiasm with an
economic integration of their own rather than the Arab-Israeli
cooperation. Secondly, the regional economic cooperation process
has hardly yielded tangible fruits for other complex reasons
than those regarding the peace process.
</P>
<P>
The Arab countries which have announced to come -- merely
for investment opportunities and access to technologies badly
needed in the region -- have either hinted a low level
representation or vowed to use the meeting to criticize the
Israeli policies.
</P>
<P>
Only three Arab countries besides the host have announced
their attendance, namely Yemen, Jordan and Kuwait. Oman, which
had promised to come, now says it is not a final decision.
</P>
<P>
This means that the actual Arab presentation at the Doha
conference would hardly maintain at the already downgraded
ministerial level and the political discussion on regional
economic framework on the agenda would have to be adjusted.
</P>
<P>
Egypt's Arab economic daily World Today said Tuesday that the
Doha meeting has failed even before its opening. Egyptian
President Hosni Mubarak said the Doha gathering would achieve
nothing and be "meaningless."
</P>
<P>
In defiance of the protest, however, Qatar said the conference
must go ahead, stressing on the economic benefit to the region as
a whole to be brought about by a galaxy of world businessmen and
investors expected to be drawn to attendance.
</P>
<P>
But the real question, many Arab analysts pointed out, is that
without progress in peace process and the ensuing Arabs'
cooperation, the economic cooperation process set forward in
Casablanca summit for a prosperous region based on the
Arab-Israeli rapport is doomed to tail away. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19971112.0085 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-11-12 </DATE_TIME>
