<HEADLINE> Manila to Train More Former Muslim Rebels </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MANILA, November 12 (Xinhua) -- The Philippine military will
start next week to train more selected members of a former major
rebel group to step up its integration into the country's Armed
Forces, a military spokesman said today.
</P>
<P>
The first batch of some 1,200 members of the Moro National
Liberation Front (MNLF) started their six-month training this June
and will complete their basic army course next month, said Captain
Slih Indanan, spokesman for Southern Command based in Mindanao.
</P>
<P>
Indanan said the next batch of MNLF trainees were previously
screened last April along with the first batch and they will also
take the basic six-month course before induction into the army.
</P>
<P>
The MNLF, the then largest Muslim rebel group in the country,
signed a landmark peace agreement with the government in September
last year, ending nearly three decade bloody war in the southern
Philippines.
</P>
<P>
Under the agreement, 5,500 MNLF fighters will be integrated
into the military and another 1,500 into the national police
force.
</P>
<P>
The integration process, vital for a lasting peace in the
southern Philippines, had experienced delays for lack of
educational qualification of some MNLF members to qualify as law
enforcers, and lack of budget allocation.
</P>
<P>
The government earlier decided to provide educational
scholarships to qualified MNLF members so they can be trained soon
and allocate more fund to step up the integration process.
</P>
</TEXT>
