<HEADLINE> Kenya Sets Dec. 29 for General Elections </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NAIROBI, November 12 (Xinhua) -- The Chairman of the Electoral
Commission Zacchaeus Chesoni announced here today that Kenya's
presidential and parliamentary elections will be held on December
29.
</P>
<P>
At a press conference, he said that all political parties must
finalize nomination of their parliamentary candidates on or
before December 7.
</P>
<P>
Presidential candidates must hand in their nomination papers
on December 3 and 4, Chesoni added.
</P>
<P>
The chairman of the electoral commission announced the
election date only two days after Kenyan President Daniel arap
Moi dissolved the 7th Parliament last Monday.
</P>
<P>
President Moi noted on December 10 that the program for the
general elections would be announced by the electoral commission
which is in charge of setting the timetable for nominations and
campaigning under the Kenya Constitution.
</P>
<P>
As Kenya's president must also be an MP, there must be a
parliamentary election to go along with a presidential poll.
</P>
<P>
Moi, 74 and in power since 1978, has already been formally
nominated by the ruling Kenya African National Union as
presidential candidate and is viewed as a favorite in the general
elections.
</P>
<P>
Observers here said that the announcement ended months of
speculation over Kenya's election date which has caused
uncertainty in business sectors.
</P>
<P>
Chesoni said that political parties would be given 23 days to
nominate their candidates who would have 20 instead of the
minimum 14 days to campaign after formal nomination. 
</P>
</TEXT>
