<HEADLINE> Manila to Release More Funds to Counter El Nino </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MANILA, November 12 (Xinhua) -- Philippine President Fidel
Ramos today announced that he will release more funds to address
the problems caused by the El Nino weather phenomenon.
</P>
<P>
At his regular press conference at the Presidential Palace,
Ramos ordered Defense Secretary Fortunato Abat, who is also
chairman of the National Disaster Coordinating Council,
Agriculture Secretary Salvador Escudero and Environment and
Natural Secretary Victor Ramos to study and submit to him a
program of about 200 million to 250 million pesos (6 to 7.6
million U.S. dollars) to address El Nino, a weather phenomenon
caused by warming Pacific waters.
</P>
<P>
El Nino can bring heavy rainfalls and flooding as well as
droughts.
</P>
<P>
Because few typhoons hit the country in the year, "so we are
addressing very, very firmly this El Nino phenomenon," he said.
</P>
<P>
Ramos said the government has already released big amounts of
funds, amounting to 1.5 billion pesos (45 million dollars) so far,
to adopt measures against El Nino.
</P>
<P>
Ramos said top priority should be given to local community
projects for irrigation, water conservation, water recycling and
water utilization such as small farm reservoirs, small water
impounding projects and shallow well tubes for irrigation.
</P>
<P>
Ramos asked the three officials to submit to him the results of
 actions they have taken no later than November 17.  
</P>
</TEXT>
