<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Doctors in Shanghai Use Acupuncture for Anaesthesia </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, November 12 (Xinhua) -- Researchers at the Shanghai
Medical University are using new anaesthesia by acupuncture in
combination with western medicine to improve the success rate of
their operations.
</P>
<P>
It has even proven successful in brain surgery, where the risk
of being handicapped or of dying is great. But, by using the new
anaesthesia, the success rate of such operations can be as high as
98 percent.
</P>
<P>
The researchers found that acupuncture can stimulate the body's
self-adjustment system to relieve pain, but often fails to provide
an overall anaesthesic effect for the part of the body being
operated on.
</P>
<P>
After several years of study, they found that using acupuncture
along with small doses of western anaesthetics can help relieve
pain both during and after the operation, and can reduce the
side-effects or risk of using large doses of drugs.
</P>
<P>
It can also help patients remain awake to co-operate with
doctors during the operation instead of being rendered unconscious
by large doses of anaesthetics. In some operations, like throat
reconstruction, co-operation by the patient is vital to the
success of the operation.
</P>
<P>
With the use of acupuncture, patients usually recover more
rapidly and have a reduced risk of complications after the
operation, the researchers say. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19971112.0093 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-11-12 </DATE_TIME>
