<HEADLINE> Hungarian Privatization Process Approaching End </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BUCHAREST, November 12 (Xinhua) -- The Hungarian privatization
process is nearing its end, with German and U.S. investors on the
top of the buyers' list.
</P>
<P>
The privatization, which started at the beginning of 1990, is
scheduled to conclude before the general elections to be held in
next May.
</P>
<P>
The total number of state-owned enterprises in Hungary has
shrunk to only five from 1,857 on January 1, 1990. The rest have
been closed, idled, merged with others or transferred to other
business operations.
</P>
<P>
The nationwide privatization proceeds in the past few years
total 1,200 billion Forints (about 6.12 billion U.S. dollars),
77 percent of which are in foreign currencies.
</P>
<P>
Only about half the revenue has entered the national treasury,
with the rest held back by local governments or lost in
transaction procedures.
</P>
<P>
Privatization has involved the sale of commercial
institutions and manufacturing businesses in large quantities,
energy businesses such as power plants, oil companies, as well as
banks and telephone companies.
</P>
<P>
Germany purchased 37.11 percent of the businesses sold, topping
the buyers' list. Second to it is the United States which has
purchased 21.66 percent. France, Austria, Belgium and the
countries from the Commonwealth of Independent States are
following behind. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
