<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Swedish Company targets Upset Stomachs </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
STOCKHOLM, November 12 (Xinhua)-- Astra, a Swedish
pharmaceuticals group, is expected to expand the sale of its
best-selling ulcer medicine Losec by 25 percent, the local press
reported today.
</P>
<P>
The main reason for the expansion is recent approval that will
permit the drug to be used in the treatment of dyspeptic
complaints, the report said.
</P>
<P>
Dyspepsia is a term used to describe various types of
indigestion, such as heartburn or stomachache, which do not
involve ulcers. The total market potential for this area, which
Astra has until now not fully exploited, is substantially larger
than that of stomach ulcers.
</P>
<P>
Astra has obtained the approval of British health authorities
for the use of Losec to treat non-diagnosed stomach pains. Similar
approvals in a number of other European countries are in the
pipeline.
</P>
<P>
Astra currently has about 5 percent of the dyspepsia
market. "If we can increase this from 5 to 10 percent, it will
have a major effect on Losec sales," said the company's
spokesman.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
