<DATE_TIME> 1997-11-12 13:24 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Netanyahu: No More Use of Canadian Passports </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JERUSALEM, November 12 (Xinhua) -- Israeli Prime Minister
Benjamin Netanyahu promised here today that Israeli agents will
never use Canadian passports any more in their overseas operations.
</P>
<P>
Netanyahu made this promise while meeting with Canadian
Foreign Minister Lloyd Axworthy who arrived here Tuesday on a
two-day visit.
</P>
<P>
The falling out between Ottawa and Jerusalem, over Israel's
Mossad's use of Canadian passports in the abortive bid to
assassinate Hamas political leader Khaled Mashaal in Amman on
September 25, did come up as expected during today's meeting
between Netanyahu and Axworthy.
</P>
<P>
Netanyahu said after the meeting that he reassured Axworthy
that Israeli agents will never use Canadian passports again in
future in overseas operations because Canada regards it as a
serious matter that can harm bilateral relations.
</P>
<P>
Canada, angered by Mossad hit men's using forged Canadian
passports in the Amman operation, recalled its ambassador from
Israel in early October. The ambassador has since returned to
Israel.
</P>
<P>
During the meeting, Axworthy asked Israel to participate in the
anti-land mine conference due to be held in Ottawa next month.
Netanyahu told Axworthy that Israel will send a delegation,
including mine experts, to the upcoming conference.
</P>
<P>
Israel is among the countries which are unwilling to sign a
treaty banning the use of mines.
</P>
<P>
On Tuesday, Axworthy met with his Israeli counterpart David
Levy.
</P>
<P>
Addressing a joint forum Tuesday sponsored by the Peres Center
for Peace and the Palestinian Center for Regional Studies,
Axworthy said Canada will continue providing material and
diplomatic support to the parties negotiating peace.
</P>
<P>
He urged the Middle East states to attend the fourth Middle
East and North Africa Economic Conference, to be held in Qatari
capital Doha on Sunday.
</P>
<P>
Many Arab countries, including Egypt, Lebanon, Syria, Saudi
Arabia, the United Arab Emirates have announced their boycott of
the conference which also includes Israel. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
