<DOCNO> XIE19971112.0102 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-11-12 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Philippine Government, Private Sector Cooperate to </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MANILA, November 12 (Xinhua) -- The Philippine government and
the private sector are working closely to solve the current
currency crisis by lowering the costs of doing business and
improving the infrastructure needed for growth.
</P>
<P>
Trade Secretary Cesar Bautista said today that the move is
aimed at sustaining investors' confidence in the strength of the
Philippine economy.
</P>
<P>
This strategy is part of the 11-point action agenda, which was
drawn during the recent multi-sectoral conference to address the
present currency crisis having plagued the country since July.
</P>
<P>
Bautista said the government and the private sector are also
trying to reduce costs that could eventually be passed on to
buyers.
</P>
<P>
He said the National Power Corporation and power distributors
are discussing lowering of power rates during non-peak hours.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, the Export Industry Development Council and the
Philippine Ports Authority have decided to review ways of cutting
costs on port handling services on November 30.
</P>
<P>
The government also began to rationalize tariffs to boost the
international competitiveness of the country's economy, Bautista
said.
</P>
<P>
The Trade and Related Matters Committee will start to review
tariffs on 22 priority sectors next month. These sectors are those
with latent competitiveness.
</P>
<P>
Bautista said his department and the Central Bank will also
intensify the monitoring of trade transaction data to better
project pending opportunities and threats.
</P>
<P>
Imports will undergo closer review by virtue of a proposed
presidential directive to ensure efficiency and relevance in order
to reduce trade deficit.
</P>
<P>
The Philippines has been hounded by a currency crisis since
July, which swept Southeast Asian nations and sent shock waves to
other regions. The Philippine peso has so far depreciated by
nearly 27 percent against the U.S. dollar.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
