<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Port Development in East China Province </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NANJING, November 12 (Xinhua) - The east China coastal province
of Jiangsu has been successful in its port improvements and
handled 20 million tons of foreign trade in the first nine months.
</P>
<P>
The volume this year is expected to reach 28 million tons,
seven times the figure of a decade ago, when the province's ports
began to open to the outside world.
</P>
<P>
In the first three quarters of this year, Jiangsu had a
container volume of over 400,000 TEUs, and 550,000 TEUs are
estimated for the whole year, a 38 percent rise over last year.
</P>
<P>
The increasing port capacity is playing a major role in the
province's foreign trade. Seven of its port cities have 90 percent
of the overseas investment.
</P>
<P>
Jiangsu has 11 Grade-1 airports, sea ports, and river ports
with overseas-oriented service. It has 110 foreign trade berths
each capable of handling 10,000-ton vessels.
</P>
<P>
Containers can be shipped from Lianyungang, Nanjing, Zhenjian,
Jiangyin, Yangzhou and Zhangjiagang to Hong Kong, Japan, the
Republic of Korea, and Europe, or can be sent by train across the
Euro-Asian Continental Bridge from Lianyungang to Rotterdam in the
Netherlands.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
