<HEADLINE> 58 PKK Rebels Killed in Southeastern Turkey </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ANKARA, November 12 (Xinhua) -- Fifty-eight rebels of the
outlawed Kurdish Workers' Party (PKK) have been killed in the
military operations by the Turkish security forces in southeastern
Turkey since November 5.
</P>
<P>
A statement issued by the office of the Emergency Regional
Rule today said that the government troops today exchanged fire
with the PKK guerrillas in Beytussabap town of Sirnak province
and shot dead 13 PKK militants in the clashes.
</P>
<P>
One security soldier was also killed and another one was
wounded in the armed clashes with the PKK in Sirnak, said the
statement.
</P>
<P>
Semi-official Anatolia news agency reported today that a total
of 58 PKK militants were killed in the military operations in the
provinces of Siirt, Sirnak and Van within one week.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, the Turkish security forces launched a cross-border
military operation in northern Iraq on November 8 in an attempt to
wipe out the PKK rebels taking shelter there.
</P>
<P>
Turkey has in recent years frequently launched cross-border
military operations in northern Iraq to eliminate the PKK
rebels in the region.
</P>
<P>
The PKK has been fighting for autonomy in eastern and
southeastern Turkey since August 1984. 
</P>
</TEXT>
