<HEADLINE> Joint Venture Operational in China's 'Copper Capital' </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HEFEI, November 12 (Xinhua) -- The Jinlong Copper Co. Ltd., the
first and largest Sino-Overseas joint venture in the nonferrous
industry, has gone into operation in China's "Copper Capital,"
Tongling City in east China's Anhui Province.
</P>
<P>
The company has a yearly capacity of 100,000 tons of copper
cathode, 375,000 tons of sulfuric acid, and turns out such
byproducts as gold and silver.
</P>
<P>
The joint venture, which is also the largest overseas-funded
enterprise in Anhui, with a total investment of 1.9 billion yuan.
</P>
<P>
The Tongling Nonferrous Metals (Group) Corp. holds 52 percent
of the shares while three Japanese companies -- Sumitomo Metal and
Mining Corp., Sumitomo Corp. and Itochu Corp. -- take up 35
percent. Hong Kong Sharpline International Corp. owns the
remaining 13 percent.
</P>
<P>
The joint venture is one of the key projects for the country's
Eighth Five-Year Plan (1991-1996), using the world's most advanced
"flash smelting" process.
</P>
<P>
The project was designed by local experts and 60 percent of its
equipment were made in China. The rest of the equipment was
imported from Japan, the United States, Finland, Austria, France,
Canada and Switzerland.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
