<HEADLINE> Pakistan Says Determined to Arrest Gunmen </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ISLAMABAD, November 12 (Xinhua) -- President Farooq Leghari
said today that the Pakistani government is determined to arrest
the gunmen who killed four Americans in Karachi this morning.
</P>
<P>
"We are determined to apprehend the criminals swiftly and award
them severe punishment," Leghari said in a condolence message to
U.S. President Bill Clinton.
</P>
<P>
Leghari said the incident in Pakistan's southern port city
"shocked us deeply."
</P>
<P>
Foreign Minister Gohar Ayub Khan also expressed his shock and
grief over the incident.
</P>
<P>
"We will leave no stone unturned in apprehending the criminals
who carried out this dastardly act and exemplary punishment would
be given to them," Gohar said in his condolence message to U.S.
Secretary of State Madeleine Albright.
</P>
<P>
The four U.S. citizens, who were on a visit in connection with
some official work at Union Texas Karachi, were gunned down by
unidentified assailants at around 8:20 a.m. on their way from
Karachi Sheraton Hotel to their office about three kilometers
away.
</P>
<P>
According to eye witnesses, the assailants were driving a red
Honda Civic, which was later found abandoned in a nearby area.
</P>
<P>
U.S. Embassy officials here declined to make any comment on the
incident, saying only that they were still gathering details of
the incident.
</P>
<P>
The incident came one day after a 12-member U.S. jury declared
a Pakistani national, Aimal Kansi, guilty of killing two agents of
the Central Intelligence Agency (CIA) and wounding three others in
the January 1993 shooting outside the CIA Headquarters.
</P>
<P>
The U.S. Embassy here Tuesday had warned all American citizens
in Pakistan to be on guard against possible retaliation after
Kansi's conviction in the U.S.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
