<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Sri Lankan Firm Fined for Customs Fraud </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
COLOMBO, November 12 (Xinhua) -- A local firm was fined 53
million rupees (898,000 U.S. dollars) by the Sri Lankan Customs
after it was found fraudulently claiming a consignment of imported
yellow split peas as red millet, Sri Lanka's national news agency
reported today.
</P>
<P>
The news agency, Lankapuvath, said the customs Tuesday foiled
the firm's attempt to evade customs duties.
</P>
<P>
The firm declared that it was importing red millet valued at
185,000 rupees (3,136 dollars), but in fact the imported goods
were 103.6 tons of yellow split peas worth 4 million rupees
(67,800 dollars).
</P>
<P>
Two partners of the firm were fined 26.4 million rupees
(447,000 dollars) each and a manager and an accountant of the
company also had to face a fine of 100,000 rupees (1,700 dollars)
each, Lankapuvath said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
