<DOCNO> XIE19971112.0123 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-11-12 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Chinese Premier Pays Courtesy Call on Japanese Emperor </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
TOKYO, November 12 (Xinhua) -- Visiting Chinese Premier Li Peng
and his wife Zhu Lin called on Japanese Emperor Akihito and
Empress Michiko here today.
</P>
<P>
The emperor said he is looking forward to the visit by Chinese
President Jiang Zemin to Japan next year.
</P>
<P>
Li conveyed regards from President Jiang to the emperor, saying
that Jiang has in principle accepted the invitation.
</P>
<P>
The emperor said this year marks the 25th anniversary of the
normalization of Japan-China relations. Li's visit will strengthen
the friendly relations and cooperation between Japan and China, he
added.
</P>
<P>
Li said the development of Sino-Japanese relations is important
not only for the Chinese and Japanese peoples but for peace and
development of the Asia-Pacific region and the world at large.
</P>
<P>
The premier said the China visit by the royal couple in 1992
played a positive role in promoting Sino-Japanese relations.
</P>
<P>
Li told the emperor that he had exchanged indepth views with
Prime Minister Ryutaro Hashimoto on how to establish
good-neighborly Sino-Japanese relations oriented to the 21st
century.
</P>
<P>
Emperor Akihito thanked the Chinese side for inviting the
Japanese crown prince and his wife to visit China next year.
</P>
<P>
Li briefed the emperor on the major events in China this year
which included the return of Hong Kong and the convening of the
15th National Congress of the Chinese Communist Party. He also
briefed the emperor on the construction of the Three Gorges dam --
China's largest-ever hydraulic engineering project.
</P>
<P>
After the meeting, the emperor and empress hosted a dinner in
honor of Premier Li and his wife.
</P>
<P>
The Chinese premier arrived in Tokyo yesterday afternoon for a
six-day official good-will visit to Japan. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
