<DATE_TIME> 1997-11-12 13:12 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Sudan Calls for Discussion on Sanctions </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
KHARTOUM, November 12 (Xinhua) -- Sudan called for convening an
international summit to discuss the economic sanctions imposed on
the Third-World nations, according to local Al-Ambaa newspaper
today.
</P>
<P>
The call came at a meeting in Khartoum Tuesday between
Abdel-Azia Shedu, deputy speaker of Sudan's National Assembly
(parliament), and Stephen Hull, head of the U.N. panel charged
with investigating sanctions on Third World countries.
</P>
<P>
Shedu emphasized Sudan's readiness to support the efforts
made by the World body in this regard, the paper said.
</P>
<P>
The U.S. administration has decided to impose stiff economic
sanctions against Sudan for what it described as sponsorship of of
terror, its effort to destabilize neighboring countries and its
abysmal record on human rights.
</P>
<P>
The paper quoted Hull as saying that he came to Sudan to
explain the objectives of the U.N. panel and discuss the
possibility of raising international lawsuits against the
sanctions that have been, or will be, imposed on the Third World
countries. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
