<DATE_TIME> 1997-11-12 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Deep-Sea Exploration in Eastern Pacific Proves Fruitful </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
GUANGZHOU, November 12 (Xinhua) -- Chinese scientists have
gleaned satisfying results in exploring for polymetallic nodule
resources in the eastern waters of the Pacific Ocean.
</P>
<P>
Scientists aboard an ocean expedition vessel collected nearly
3.5 tons of polymetallic nodule resources and 467 kilograms of
cobalt-rich nodule minerals during their half-year trip, according
to Zhang Guozhen, one of the chief scientists on the expedition.
</P>
<P>
The vessel, named Marine Four, left Guangzhou on May 20 and
returned today.
</P>
<P>
In 1991, China was registered with the United Nations as a
pioneering investor in international sea-bed exploration,
acquiring the rights to explore a polymetallic nodule area
covering 150,000 square kilometers in the eastern waters of the
Pacific.
</P>
<P>
This was the seventh trip for the Marine Four to the area for
scientific surveys.
</P>
<P>
During the latest expedition, scientists also conducted
seismological surveys along a total length of 1,034 km, magnetic
surveys along 3,444 km, and sea-bed topographical surveys in an
area covering 30,000 sq. km., Zhang said.
</P>
<P>
With previous and future investigations, an area covering
75,000 sq. km. will be used for China's commercial exploration in
the next century.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
