<HEADLINE> NAOC Chief Proposes Compromise to End Downhill Course Row </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
TOKYO, November 12 (Xinhua) -- The top offical of the Nagano
Winter Olympics proposed on Wednesday that the start for the
disputed downhill course could be raised if both the starting gate
and the course itself are outside a national park.
</P>
<P>
Nagano Organising Committee (NAOC) director-general Makoto
Kobayashi, proposed the compromise to try to end the debate over a
bid by the International Ski Federation (FIS) to raise the start
of the men's Alpine event by 120 meters to 1,800 meters.
</P>
<P>
Kobayashi's comments came one day after top officials of NAOC,
Japan Olympic Committee and Ski Association officials decided to
set up a special committee to resolve the long-standing row.
</P>
<P>
But SAJ director for international relations Aki Murasato said
on Wednesday that the compromise was not enough.
</P>
<P>
FIS and the SAJ have complained for years that the course, with
a racing time of about one minute 30 seconds, was too short to be
a true Olympic test. 
</P>
</TEXT>
