<DATE_TIME> 1997-11-12 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Sri Lanka to Install Anti-Missile Systems on Aircraft </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
COLOMBO, November 12 (Xinhua) -- The Sri Lankan Air Force
(SLAF) is considering to equip all its aircraft with automatic
anti-missile systems after one of its Mi-24 chopper was brought
down by a rebel missile Monday, military sources said here today.
</P>
<P>
Two pilots were killed after a missile fired by the Liberation
Tigers of Tamil Eelam (LTTE) hit the Mi-24 chopper over Vavuniya
in the northeastern coastal area.
</P>
<P>
The sources quoted high-ranking officers of the Air Force as
saying that they are looking into the possibility of equipping all
the air force craft with anti-missile systems, which cost 700,000
U.S. dollars each.
</P>
<P>
The sources didn't mention how many aircraft have not been
equipped with such systems.
</P>
<P>
An officer at the Air Force headquarters in Colombo said that
so far half of the air force aircraft are not equipped with
automatic anti-missile systems.
</P>
<P>
The officer, who asked not to be identified, said the Air Force
is in the process of installing the systems to its fleet.
</P>
<P>
Military intelligence reports said the LTTE had obtained many
missiles recently, posing a great threat to the Air Force.
</P>
<P>
The Air Force today said initial investigations have found that
in Monday's attack, the LTTE rebels had fired a total of five
missiles at the fleet of four military choppers en route from
Vavuniya to Elephant Pass in the north.
</P>
<P>
The ill-fated Mi-24 crashed into the Kokkilai Lagoon in the
northeastern coastal area after it was hit by one missile. The
other three Mi-17s evaded the rest missiles due to the activation
of automatic anti-missile systems.
</P>
<P>
About 100 soldiers were on board the three choppers at the time
of attack.
</P>
<P>
Air Force Commander Air Marshal Oliver Ranasinghe has said that
missile attacks by the rebels would not deter further air force
engagement in the on-going ethnic war.
</P>
<P>
The war has been going on for 14 years between the government
troops and the LTTE, which is fighting for an independent state of
their own in the north and east of the country.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
