<DOCNO> XIE19971112.0140 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-11-12 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Macao Sees More Rainfall This Year </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MACAO, November 12 (Xinhua) -- Macao has recorded a total
rainfall of 2,633.4 millimeters so far this year, the highest
since 1983.
</P>
<P>
Fong Soi Kun, deputy director of the Macao Geophysics and
Meteorological Observatory, told the Macao Daily News that this
year's rainfall was 789 millimeters more than the same period in
normal years.
</P>
<P>
He said that the increased rainfall was attributed to the
strong effect of the El Nino phenomenon, which brought downpours
to Macao.
</P>
<P>
In addition, the effect of this year's El Nino was just at its
beginning stage, he said, adding that it will last until next
year.
</P>
<P>
The average annual rainfall between 1961 and 1990 was 2,031.4
millimeters, and the highest rainfall recorded was 3,041.4
millimeters in 1982, which was also the result of the El Nino
effect.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
