<DATE_TIME> 1997-11-12 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Central Bank Increasing Supervision Over Commercial Banks </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, November 12 (Xinhua) -- The People's Bank of China,
the nation's central bank, today issued provisional rules
governing the installation of the board of supervisors for
state-owned commercial banks.
</P>
<P>
The central bank's board of supervisors monitors state-owned
commercial banks approved by the State Council. The board is
responsible for supervising, maintaining and increasing the value
of state-owned assets controlled by banks.
</P>
<P>
The board is charged with reviewing the financial reports of
state-owned commercial banks, as well as supervising and
evaluating the quality of credit assets and asset-to-liability
ratios.
</P>
<P>
The central bank is also authorized to supervise and review the
performance of chairpersons and presidents working for state-owned
banks.
</P>
<P>
The board of supervisors is mandated to report to the central
bank on a regular basis. The board consists of representatives
from the central bank, the Ministry of Finance, the State Economic
and Trade Commission, the State Audit Administration, the State
Property Administration and state-owned commercial banks, as well
as economic and legal experts.
</P>
<P>
The provisional rules set forth detailed stipulations on the
qualifications, rights and obligations of board members.
</P>
<P>
Observers note that the establishment of the board of
supervisors for state-owned banks will be of great significance to
improving overall banking operations. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
