<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Australian Stocks Finish Weaker </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CANBERRA, November 12 (Xinhua) -- The Australian share market
finished lower today, dragged down by depressed Asian markets and
wary in the lead-up to tonight's Federal Reserve meeting in the
United States.
</P>
<P>
Reynolds &AMP; Co's Peter Struk said despite overseas influences,
the all ordinaries closing down 13.1 points at 2,510.9 "wasn't a
bad result."
</P>
<P>
"The Australian market is a little bit jittery with the Federal
Reserve meeting in the U.S. tonight," Struk said.
</P>
<P>
Analysts generally do not expect the U.S. Federal Reserve's
Open Market Committee meeting tonight to tighten monetary policy
in the United States following the volatility on Southeast Asian
markets.
</P>
<P>
The all industrials index lost 9.4 points to 4,215.9 while the
all resources index slumped 17.4 to 1,159.7.
</P>
<P>
The banking index closed 29.8 points stronger at 5,225.7.
</P>
<P>
The Commonwealth lost three cents to 17.07 Australian dollars
at the close after announcing its share buyback while the National
Australia bank climbed 6.5 cents to 20.778 Australian dollars.
</P>
<P>
ANZ bank was 18 cents higher at 9.73 Australian dollars, while
Westpac bank climbed six cents to 8.74 Australian dollars.
</P>
<P>
Profit taking drove some of the major resource stocks down with
mining giant BHP losing 45 cents to 14.45 Australian dollars.
</P>
<P>
The gold index closed 11.6 cents weaker at 1,027.0 points with
spot gold bullion trading down 60 US cents at 309.10 US dollars.
</P>
<P>
National turnover was 226.77 million shares worth 446,25
million US dollars with falls outweighing rises 522 to 419.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
