<DOCNO> XIE19971112.0155 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-11-12 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Philippines to Solve Traffic Problem in Capital </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MANILA, November 12 (Xinhua) -- The Philippine government will
start a 22 million U.S. dollars rehabilitation of the ageing
traffic signal system in Manila to ease traffic chaos in the city.
</P>
<P>
Upgrading the antiquated traffic signal system is a vital part
of the government's plan to solve the protracted traffic problem,
Godofredo Galano, director of the Traffic Engineering Center under
the Department of Public Works and Highways, told reporters today.
</P>
<P>
The ageing traffic signal system has been blamed as one of the
causes for traffic chaos in the capital city, one of the worst in
Asia's mega-cities, he said.
</P>
<P>
Galano said motorists and commuters who are not satisfied with
the traffic signal system tend to disregard traffic rules,
resulting into chaos.
</P>
<P>
"When everybody is satisfied with the (traffic signal) system,
then everybody will follow the traffic rule and regulations, there
will be an orderly traffic flow," he explained.
</P>
<P>
The fixed time traffic signal system, which was installed in
1977, has become so ineffective that it could not cope with the
demand of the growing volume of both the vehicles and the
population in the metropolis.
</P>
<P>
Under the fixed-time system, all of Metro Manila's 450 traffic
lights are synchronized and that changing of traffic lights take
at least 15 minutes regardless of the volume of the traffic.
</P>
<P>
Galanao expected the traffic flow will improve after the
problem of the intersection has been solved.
</P>
<P>
With 35 percent of the total rehabilitation cost granted by
Australia, Metro Manila will adopt the intelligent traffic system
called the Sydney Adoptive Traffic Signal System, a new system
which can automatically respond by needs.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
