<DOCNO> XIE19971112.0161 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-11-12 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Parties in Nigeria Urged to Draft Abacha as </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LAGOS, November 12 (Xinhua) -- Nigeria's Minister of Special
Duties Wada Nas has called on the country's five political
parties to draft the head of the military government, General
Sani Abacha as their common candidate in next year's presidential
election.
</P>
<P>
According to press reports, the minister said in a statement
Tuesday in Abuja that such a move is allowed by the draft
constitution of 1995.
</P>
<P>
The 1995 draft constitution was forwarded to the Abacha
government on June 27 of that year after exactly a year's work by
the constitution conference. But until now it has not been
published, despite repeated calls by some politicians.
</P>
<P>
The minister explained that such a move is necessary
because "no credible candidates have shown interest to contest",
despite Abacha's call on Nigerians to feel absolutely free to
express their ambitions within the five registered parties.
</P>
<P>
Wada Nas said that even if Abacha succeed himself in
October 1998, there will be no presidency of the present statue,
because his current power as the head of state will be shared by
the president and the prime minister.
</P>
<P>
He, therefore, argued that Abacha's stay in power beyond 1998
should not be regarded as the continuation of the domination of
power by the north.
</P>
<P>
Commenting on the arising call on Abacha to contest, the
minister said people has the right to oppose the call, but it
will be wrong for such people to vilify those who are in support
of Abacha.
</P>
<P>
As the military government's transition to civil rule program
draws nearer, Abacha's intention has become a concern to
more and more people.
</P>
<P>
Abacha has said that it is not new for military heads
of state to shed their uniform and become civilian presidents,
and that his candidacy is to be decided by the Nigerian people.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19971112.0162 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-11-12 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> China to Host Environmental Protection Exhibition </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, November 12 (Xinhua) -- China will host a large-scale
exhibition on environmental protection from Dec. 5 to 9 in Beijing.
</P>
<P>
The China International Environmental Protection Exhibition
will show technology and equipment for pollution control, clean
production, recycling resources, protecting the ecology and
monitoring the environment. The exhibition is designed to promote
the development of China's environmental industry through wide
exchanges and cooperation.
</P>
<P>
Representatives from all the provinces, municipalities,
autonomous regions and some of the ministries will attend the
exhibition. In addition, nearly 60 companies from 14 countries
including the United States and Japan have applied for
participation.
</P>
<P>
"Companies in the environmental circle at home and abroad are
eager to take part in the show, and the 10,000 square-meter
exhibition area is in short supply," said an official with the
organizers, the State Bureau of Environmental Protection and the
Chinese Association of Environmental Protection Industry.
</P>
<P>
During the exhibition, a China-Europe environmental symposium
and two lectures on China's pollution control projects and
international cooperation in the environmental protection industry
will be arranged.
</P>
<P>
China's environmental protection industry has more than 7,500
companies, of which 80 percent are small firms. The annual output
of the industry is 30 billion yuan (about 3.7 billion
U.S. dollars).  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
