<HEADLINE> Major News Items in Leading French Newspapers </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
PARIS, November 12 (Xinhua) -- The following are major news
items in leading French newspapers today:
</P>
<P>
Liberation:
</P>
<P>
-- Algeria Tuesday expressed regret that the French government
"backed" the demonstration in support of Algerian people held on
Monday in Paris and several other French cities, saying that this
was in contradiction with repeated promise by France not to
interfere into the internal affairs of Algeria.
</P>
<P>
-- French President Jacques Chirac today began a state visit to
Vietnam, during which he will insist on the need to reinforce an
economic space for French-speaking countries and to "resist" the
universalizaton of the American culture. Several economic
contracts will be signed during the visit, including one on
installing 500,000 telephone lines in Ho Chi-Minh City by the
France Telecom company.
</P>
<P>
Le Figaro:
</P>
<P>
-- Iraq refused to yield on Tuesday as the United States
pressed the U.N. Security Council to impose new sanctions against
Baghdad for its decision to exclude Americans from the operations
on disarmament of the United Nations. American officers on board
the Nimitz aircraft carrier which is cruising the Persian Gulf
have warned that if Iraq shoots down the U.S. U2 spy plane, "the
risk of confrontation will be very high" and "chances of
retaliation will be very probable."
</P>
<P>
-- According to a survey by le Figaro on the eve of the
Francophone summit to be held in Hanoi, the French language is on
the decline in Africa but on the rise in Canada. In Algeria, the
French language remains a major channel of communication despite a
law voted in 1992 making the Arabic the official language. In
Canada, the federal government uses French language as a weapon to
resist culture invasion from its gigantic neighbor. 
</P>
</TEXT>
