<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Philippines to Get Free of IMF Supervision: Official </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MANILA, November 12 (Xinhua) -- The Philippines is set to exit
from the decades-long supervision of its economic development by
the International Monetary Fund (IMF) by December this year with
the enactment of a new oil deregulation law.
</P>
<P>
The Legislative-Executive Development Advisory Council chaired
by President Fidel Ramos has reached a consensus that the
Philippines should exit by December, Finance Secretary Roberto de
Ocampo was quoted today by local TV as saying.
</P>
<P>
De Ocampo urged the Congress to come up with a new oil
deregulation law in time for a decent graduation of the country
from the 23rd or last IMF supervision program.
</P>
<P>
Central Bank Governor Gabriel Singson earlier warned that the
country's exit from the program may be delayed again because of
the recent ruling of the Supreme Court nullifying the
nine-month-old oil deregulation law.
</P>
<P>
But de Ocampo, who is also vice chairman of the Philippine
negotiating panel with the IMF, said he does not see the need for
an extension of the program.
</P>
<P>
Congress leaders have pledged to rush a revised oil
deregulation bill expected to level the playing field between
existing oil companies and new entrants.
</P>
<P>
On October 30, the High Tribunal overwhelmingly ruled to
abolish the oil law on the ground that it is unconstitutional by
allowing the country's three dominant oil companies to gain
monopoly of the industry.
</P>
<P>
Under the law, the government will no longer regulate oil
prices and pay subsidy to the oil industry, and the three major
oil firms can adjust oil prices freely. The deregulation of the
oil industry is part of the IMF program.
</P>
<P>
The Philippines, which has been under the IMF guidance for 35
years, was supposed to be free from the IMF this June after
meeting all the criteria set in the last program.
</P>
<P>
But the country's graduation was delayed due to the failure of
the Congress to pass the final component of the Comprehensive Tax
Reform Package (CTRP), which is designed to boost the government's
tax revenues.
</P>
<P>
The tax reform bill is now being deliberated by the Bicameral
Conference Committee and is expected to pass before the Congress
goes on its annual Christmas vacation on November 27.
</P>
<P>
The country had already passed most of the performance criteria
of the IMF, including the base money level, net international
gross reserves and external borrowings, in the third quarter.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
