<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Indonesia to Free Itself From Monetary Crisis </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JAKARTA, November 12 (Xinhua) -- Indonesia will free itself
from the current monetary crisis and will be stronger than before
the crisis, Managing Director of the International Monetary Fund
(IMF) Michel Camdessus said here today.
</P>
<P>
Speaking at a press conference here after meeting with
President Soeharto, the IMF chief said the rupiah (Indonesian
national currency), which has been hit badly in the monetary
crisis since July this year, will recover. "Of course, the
economic growth will slow down in the years to come," he added.
</P>
<P>
However, he noted, Indonesia needs to be transparent and
responsible in managing its state budget to enable it to gain
confidence and credibility.
</P>
<P>
"How can we build confidence and credibility without
transparency and responsibility?" Camdessus said.
</P>
<P>
Camdessus, who arrived here Tuesday afternoon for a two-day
visit, said "it is impossible to build a nation in just one week
and Indonesia is still in this process."
</P>
<P>
He expressed his confidence that the outcome of a transparent
and responsible management could be seen in three years.
</P>
<P>
According to Camdessus, economic management during a monetary
crisis should have three factors: the first is a stable and
reliable monetary policy; the second is a restructurization policy
in the financial and banking sectors; and the third is a policy
that aims to reduce monopolistic practices, increase the number of
state companies floating their shares in the stock market to
increase their efficiency; and attract more investors.
</P>
<P>
He held that some of these policies have already been
implemented by Indonesia.
</P>
<P>
The monetary crisis in the Southeast Asian region has caused
the rupiah to lose about 40 percent against the US dollar.
</P>
<P>
He said every crisis is a mixture of opportunities and dangers.
</P>
<P>
The IMF chief predicted that Indonesia's economic growth will
be stable after 1998.
</P>
<P>
"The country's economic growth in 1997 and 1998 will slow due
to the crisis. But its growth will surpass these years in 1999 and
2000," he added.
</P>
<P>
The IMF announced an aid package for Indonesia last month of
about 23 billion US dollars to help the country implement its
reform program. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19971112.0177 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-11-12 </DATE_TIME>
