<HEADLINE> Johannesburg's Residents Urged to Save Water </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JOHANNESBURG, November 12 (Xinhua) -- The Johannesburg
municipal authorities have urged people living in the
Johannesburg region to use water sparingly during hot spells
after two reservoirs run empty last weekend.
</P>
<P>
Despite the cooler weather being experienced, the appeal
remained valid as the empty reservoirs needed to fill up again,
local daily the Citizen today quoted a municipal spokesman as saying.
</P>
<P>
Many northern and eastern suburbs were left without water for
up to 48 hours after two reservoirs ran empty last weekend.
</P>
<P>
Graham Pearson, Chief Engineer of Water Operation in
Johannesburg, said the heat wave caused the highest water
consumption for a Sunday in 30 years.
</P>
<P>
In mid-October, South Africa's Department of Water Affairs
said South Africa, which was predicted to be struck by the El
Nino weather phenomenon in 1997-98, should not dry up
water reserves in the country.
</P>
<P>
El Nino, is expected to cause a warming the Pacific Ocean, and
will exert a generally negative impact on South Africa's summer
rainfall. It plunged the country into its worst drought in
1992-93, costing the economy more than two billion U.S. dollars.
</P>
</TEXT>
