<HEADLINE> Guangzhou Target for Regional Financial Center </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
GUANGZHOU, November 12 (Xinhua) -- Guangzhou city, capital of
south Guangdong province which pioneered China's opening up
drive, is poised to become a financial center in the Pearl River
Delta.
</P>
<P>
Under an ambitious program drawn up by the city government,
Guangzhou will build itself into a regional financial center in
the Pearl River Delta by the year 2000.
</P>
<P>
The delta, adjacent to Hong Kong and Macao, is one of China's
economic powerhouses.
</P>
<P>
By the end of the century, Guangzhou expects to play a bigger
role as a regional financial center in fund-raising, foreign
exchange trading, insurance, financial information,
accounts-clearing and training of financial personnel.
</P>
<P>
Guangzhou ranks third after Shanghai and Beijing in terms of
overall economic strength, which consolidated the city's efforts
towards a regional financial center.
</P>
<P>
In the first nine months of this year, Guangzhou registered a
GDP of 114.2 billion yuan.
</P>
<P>
The city had had 2,300 financial institutions by the end of
last year and dozens of foreign banks or their representative
offices.  
</P>
</TEXT>
