<HEADLINE> Manila, Muslim Rebels Start Eighth Round Peace Talks </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MANILA, November 12 (Xinhua) -- The Philippine government and
the rebel Moro Islamic Liberation Front (MILF) today started their
eighth round low-level peace talks in a southern Philippine city,
reports reaching here said.
</P>
<P>
The meeting was being held at a university in Marawi City,
capital of Lanao del Sur province in central Mindanao, Ghadzali
Jaafar, MILF vice chairman for political affairs, was quoted as
saying.
</P>
<P>
The government peace panel was led by newly-installed chief
negotiator Orlando Soriano and Maj. Gen. Joselin Nazareno,
commander of the Army's Fourth Infantry Division based in central
Mindanao.
</P>
<P>
And the rebel negotiating team was headed by Uztads Abduladiz
Mimbantas, MILF vice chairman for internal affairs, who replaced
Jaafar as the chief rebel negotiator.
</P>
<P>
During the two-day meeting, the two sides are expected to sign
the ground rules for implementing a comprehensive ceasefire
agreement in entire Mindanao.
</P>
<P>
They will also discuss the public executions of alleged
criminals by the MILF last month and a recent attack on a military
camp in Maguindanao province.
</P>
<P>
Earlier reports said both sides expressed optimism that an
agreement on truce ground rules and principles would be signed at
the end of the meeting.
</P>
<P>
The MILF and the government began their exploratory peace talks
in January this year and made a breakthrough in July by signing
the preliminary general truce accord.
</P>
<P>
But the two sides have failed to agree on ground rules for
carrying out the agreement due to the public execution of several
alleged criminals by the MILF last month.
</P>
<P>
The MILF, a breakaway faction of the larger Moro National
Liberation Front (MNLF), has fought the government for more than
two decades for a separate Islamic state in Mindanao.
</P>
<P>
The MILF is currently the largest anti-government force with an
estimated 12,000 fighters. The MNLF signed a peace accord with
Manila last year.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19971112.0182 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-11-12 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Wild Animals, Plants Under Well Protection In Hainan </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HAIKOU, November 12 (Xinhua) -- Hainan Province, China's
largest special economic zone, has achieved marked results in
protecting wild animals and plants.
</P>
<P>
The afforestation area of mangroves in Hainan, south China, now
stands at 30,000 mu (1,800 hectares), with 18 varieties, or 58
percent of the country's total kinds of mangroves.
</P>
<P>
Population figures are also increasing markedly for some wild
animals, including black-crowned gibbons.
</P>
<P>
Hainan, the only tropical region in China, boasts rich wild
animal and plant resources. The province has over 4,600 varieties
of vascular bundle plants, with 630 plants indigenous to
Hainan. There are 561 terrestrial vertebrates, with 35 indigenous
species.
</P>
<P>
A recent study shows that in the province's Wuzhi Mountain
Nature Reserve live 107 rare animals, such as clouded leopards,
sambar, jungle fowl, silver pheasants and black-crowned gibbons.
</P>
<P>
Years ago, the number of many rare animals and plants dropped
drastically due to over-killing and poaching. The situation was
put to an end with the establishment of increasing number of
nature reserves in recent years.
</P>
<P>
Statistics show that the province has 73 natural and ecological
protection zones, with an area of 159,800 hectares, or 4.7 percent
of the province's land area.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19971112.0183 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-11-12 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Earliest Purple Pigment Discovered in Northwest China </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
XI'AN, November 12 (Xinhua) -- The earliest purple pigment ever
used by human beings has been discovered by a group of Chinese and
German archaeologists researching the famed terracotta warriors of
the Qing Dynasty (221-207 B.C.) in Xi'an, capital of northwest
China's Shaanxi Province.
</P>
<P>
From the samples of the coloring used on the clothes of the
ancient terracotta warriors, archaeologists found copper barium
silicate, a kind of purple dye used by Chinese 2,100 years
ago.
</P>
<P>
Experts say the material has never been found before in ancient
western paintings, but it's still not clear whether the dye is
natural or synthetic.
</P>
<P>
In 1983, two experts from the United States discovered a
similar type of synthetic dye used to paint some cultural relics
of the Han Dynasty (206 B.C.-220 A.D.).  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19971112.0184 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-11-12 09:29 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Jordan Against Military Action, Sanctions on Iraq </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
AMMAN, November 12 (Xinhua) -- Jordanian Foreign Minister Fayez
Tarawneh said here today that Jordan is against any military
action as well as new sanctions on Iraq.
</P>
<P>
Tarawneh made the remark late Tuesday night at a joint press
conference with visiting Foreign Minister of Luxembourg Jacques
Poos, whose country holds the rotating presidency of the European
Union (EU).
</P>
<P>
Poos arrived here Tuesday from Cairo, Egypt. He is on a
four-day regional tour at the head of an EU delegation, which will
also take him to Israel, the Palestinian self-rule territories and
Syria.
</P>
<P>
Tarawneh said there should not be any military action against
Iraq, because it would ravage the living of the ordinary people
rather than bend the policy of the regime.
</P>
<P>
Jordan is also opposed to imposing new sanctions on Iraq, for
the sanctions usually affect the people, not the regime, he
said. Poos expressed the same idea.
</P>
<P>
"As we can see, seven years of U.N. sanctions have little
effect on the Iraqi government, but rather destroyed the living of
the ordinary people," Tarawneh said, adding that the crisis
between Baghdad and Washington should be solved through diplomatic
means.
</P>
<P>
The crisis could be settled only after both sides put up
dialogue and Iraq complies with all the related U.N. Security
Council resolutions, Tarawneh added.
</P>
<P>
Jordan's King Hussein and Crown Prince Hassan have said that
the crisis should be ended in a way that can guarantee the
sovereignty and territorial integrity of Iraq as well as pave the
way for implementation of U.N. Security Council's resolutions and
the lifting of sanctions imposed on Iraq after its 1990 invasion
of Kuwait.
</P>
<P>
Baghdad faces a showdown with the U.S. and U.N. by questioning
Washington's domination of U.N. weapons inspection missions in
Iraq and requesting U.N. sanctions be lifted. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
