<DATE_TIME> 1997-11-12 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> China Rescues Historical Relics in Three Gorge Project Areas (1) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, November 12 (Xinhua) -- The work to rescue historical
relics along the Three Gorges of the Yangtze River has been
accelerated.
</P>
<P>
In the region which is to be affected by the Yangtze River
after the damming of the Three Gorges there are 1,282 ancient
relics sites, with 453 artifacts on ground and 829 underground.
</P>
<P>
According to the relics rescuing and protection plan, 4.5
billion yuan is needed to remove and excavate some key relics
sites including Zhang Fei Temple, Shibaozai Protection Dam, Baidi
Town and the Rock-carving site at Qutang Gorge.
</P>
<P>
Since 1993, more than 300 archaeologists and workers have
conducted searches for relics in over 20 cities and counties from
Yichang city in Hubei Province to Chongqing municipality.
</P>
<P>
In September, professors and students from the Archaeological
Department of Jilin University arrived at Fengjie and Badong
counties of Chongqing to begin excavating the relics sites.
</P>
<P>
Soon after, professors and students from six other
universities, including Beijing University and Sichuan Union
University, joined in.
</P>
<P>
In Yunyang County, archaeologists from Sichuan Union University
have been working at the tomb sites of the ancient "Ba People" and
have also found building relics of the Han Dynasty (206 B.C.-220).
</P>
<P>
The archaeologists from Beijing University drew up a six-year
plan to complete the relics excavation work in Zhongxian County.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19971112.0187 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-11-12 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> China Rescues Historical Relics in Three Gorge Project Areas (2) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
Numerous large-scale projects are going on in Hubei Province in
central China in an attempt to salvage a number of ruins of
historical relics in the Three Gorges project area.
</P>
<P>
Archaeologists have proved that Hubei has 130 on ground and 63
underground ruins of historical relices in the to-be-submerged
region.
</P>
<P>
Currently more than 100 teachers and students from Wuhan
University, Jilin University, Shandong University, Xiamen
University and Nanjing University are working at the sites to
assist with the urgent recovery of the historic items.
</P>
<P>
Hubei provincial government had allocated more than 10 million
yuan (1.2 million dollars) in funding for the project by the end
of August.
</P>
<P>
Archaeologists have basically excavated three large ruins and
unearthed quite a number of historical relics dating back to the
Eastern Zhou Dynasty (770 B.C. to 256 B.C.) in Zigui County.
</P>
<P>
In Xingshan County, 13 tombs and three caves from the Han
Dynasty (206 B.C. to 220 A.D.) have been unearthed, while in
Badong County, archaeologists are busily uncovering nine
underground ruins.
</P>
<P>
Wuhan University, a leading state university in Hubei, has
enrolled dozens of students for a two-year course of study on
archaeology which focuses specifically on the Three Gorges Project
areas, in a bid to provide more specially-trained personnel for
the province.
</P>
<P>
Nearly all of the experts at the Yichang Museum are working at
the various sites to collect information on the Shang Dynasty
(some 16 century B.C. to 11 Century B.C.).
</P>
<P>
Chinese experts believe that the Three Gorge Project areas may
become a cradle for fostering future archaeologists.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
