<HEADLINE> Zambia to Improve Investment Incentives </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LUSAKA, November 12 (Xinhua) -- Zambia will amend the
Investmentr Act to improve investment incentives, Zambian
Minister of Commerce, Industry and Trade, Alfeyo Hambayi, has said.
</P>
<P>
The Post today quoted Algeyo Hambayi as saying Tuesday that
Zambia's "investment strategies should give priority to sectors
with great potential for growth and employment creation."
</P>
<P>
These sectors will include agriculture and food processing,
tourism and manufacuring generally, Hambayi said at a one-day
Zambia Industrial Partnership Council workshop.
</P>
<P>
He said he wuold like to see priority given to the development
of the micro, small and medium-scale sectors which he believes
have the greatest potential for job creation, income generation
and poverty eradication.
</P>
<P>
The ministry is finalizing arrangements for disbursement of
the 45 million U.S.Dollars credit from the World Bank, which will
benefit local entreprenures, said the paper.
</P>
<P>
Hambayi hailed the newly established Industrial Partnership
Council as "very important" to bring about industrializatin in
the country.
</P>
<P>
"Experience has shown that our failure to achieve our
industrialization objective has been largely due to our inability
to initiate the obvious measures required and to pursue and
implement effective policies," the minister said. 
</P>
