<HEADLINE> Uganda to Resettle Landless People </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
KAMPALA, November 12 (Xinhua) -- Ugandan government is making
its efforts to resettle landless people in Mukono district in
central Uganda, The New Vision reported today.
</P>
<P>
Hope Kivemgere, Press Secretary for the Ugandan president,told
the paper Tuesday that the presidential office had bought 600
acres of land in the central region to host the landless,
destitute and displaced people all over the country.
</P>
<P>
The land was bought by the Presidential Donations Fund.
</P>
<P>
The land did not belong to the president, she stressed.
</P>
<P>
Francis Oryem Odwong, a local council chairman of Mukono
District, said that an officer in charge of welfare in the
presidential office already gave the authorities of the district
a list of 33 families who will resettle on the land.
</P>
<P>
Uganda has some 60,000 displaced people in the north due to
the rebel activities by the Lord's Resistance Army. 
</P>
