<DOCNO> XIE19971112.0201 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-11-12 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Zambia to Import Maize for Food Reserve </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LUSAKA, November 12 (Xinhua) -- Zambia has signed a deal to
secure 100,000 tons of white maize from the United States to
replenish its strategic food reserve, Times of Zambia reported
today.
</P>
<P>
The paper quoted Chance Kabaghe, Chief Executive of Food
Reserve Agency (FRA), as saying Tuesday that under the deal,
which was signed on Monday, the first batch of 25,000 tons will
be shipped to Zambia in a week.
</P>
<P>
Kabaghe said that the consignment brings Zambia's total maize
imports to 170,000 tons as against the total deficit of 270,000
tons. Earlier last month, Zambia bought 70,000 tons of maize from
Zimbabwe.
</P>
<P>
The 100,000 tons of maize from the U.S., said Kabaghe, will
form part of the country's strategic food reserve in fighting
against an upcoming critical shortage of maize in December.
</P>
<P>
The Zambian government has decided to appropriate about 37
million U.S dollars to import altogether 270,000 tons of white
maize to fill the demand gap caused by reduction of output in the
country during the 1996-1997 agricultural season.
</P>
<P>
This move is absolutely necessary in the country, where maize
is a staple for the people, in view of not only the production
shortfall but also the impending drought as a result of El Nino
phenomenon during the coming season. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
