<DOCNO> XIE19971112.0203 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-11-12 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Shenzhen to Tighten Controls on Use of Land </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
SHENZHEN, November 12 (Xinhua) -- Shenzhen, in south China's
Guangdong Province, plans to tighten controls on the use of land,
according to a local official in charge of city planning and land.
</P>
<P>
Liu Jiasheng, director of the City Planning and Land
Administration, said the city will increase proportion of land
available for tenders or auctions, and will introduce effective
measures to control leases.
</P>
<P>
He said the goal of strengthening controls is to improve
economic returns from land use in Shenzhen, China's first special
economic zone, and ensure the healthy development of the city's
real estate market.
</P>
<P>
Some 4.5 million sq. m. of land allotted to developers has
remained idle for an extended period of time, according to Liu.
</P>
<P>
The city has also recorded a high vacancy rate for housing
built for the open market, with total floor space standing at
2.73 million square meters.
</P>
<P>
Lax controls on the land supply and the lack of long-term
planning for real estate development are blamed for the negative
effects on the city's real estate market.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
