<BODY>
<HEADLINE> China to Continue to Develop Friendly Ties With Japan </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
TOKYO, November 12 (Xinhua) -- Chinese Premier Li Peng said
here today that the Chinese government will continue to pursue the
policy of developing friendly relations with Japan.
</P>
<P>
China, he said, is willing to make joint and unremitting
efforts with the Japanese government and the Japanese people in
seeking the goal of maintaining Sino-Japanese friendship from
generation to generation.
</P>
<P>
He said that it is more important than ever for China and
Japan, both important nations in the region, to establish and
develop long-term and good neighborly ties oriented to the 21st
century when the world is moving rapidly toward multipolarization
and Asia's status is becoming more prominent.
</P>
<P>
Li made the remarks in meetings with leaders of three
Japanese political parties here this morning.
</P>
<P>
The three statesmen are Takako Doi, leader of the Social
Democratic Party, Ichiro Ozawa, leader of the New Frontier Party,
and Naoto Kan, representative of the Democratic Party.
</P>
<P>
Li told the party leaders that the purpose of his visit is to
work together with the Japanese side to help establish the
long-term good-neighborly ties between the two countries.
</P>
<P>
In the meeting with Doi, Li said the Social Democratic Party
has maintained good relations with China over a long period of
time and has contributed to the growth of Sino-Japanese relations.
</P>
<P>
He said that the Social Democratic Party has remained "an
important and positive force" to support Sino-Japanese friendship
since the two countries normalized their relations 25 years ago.
</P>
<P>
Li also noted that the Social Democratic Party has always stuck
to "a clear-cut and correct position" on such important issues as
history and Taiwan issue.
</P>
<P>
He said he hopes the Social Democratic Party would play an even
greater role in promoting Sino-Japanese friendship.
</P>
<P>
Doi said it is most important for the Asian region to maintain
peace and trust among different countries, adding that Japan-China
friendly relations constitute an important part in this regard.
</P>
<P>
She said her party will continue to make effort in promoting
the exchanges and cooperation between the two countries.
</P>
<P>
Doi also extended congratulations to the success of the 15th
National Congress of the Communist Party of China.
</P>
<P>
Li said when meeting with Ozawa that the New Frontier Party has
established good relations of exchanges with the Chinese Communist
Party.
</P>
<P>
Many members of the New Frontier Party have been working hard
to promote Sino-Japanese friendship for a long time, Li said,
adding that these people have played a positive role in helping
enhance the friendship between the two peoples, particularly the
exchanges between the two countries' younger generations.
</P>
<P>
Ozawa said the New Frontier Party supports China's policies of
reform and opening up to the outside world.
</P>
<P>
Li said he was happy to meet Kan and told him that China
attaches importance to the development of relations with the
Democratic Party of Japan.
</P>
<P>
The Chinese side appreciates the positive attitude taken by the
Democratic Party in developing Japan-China relations ever since
its founding, Li said.
</P>
<P>
Kan said Japan once brought great sufferings to the Chinese
people although the two countries enjoy a long history of friendly
exchanges. He added that Japan should seriously examine itself in
this regard.
</P>
<P>
As a member of Asia, Kan said, Japan should maintain friendly
relations with its neighboring countries. He added that the
Democratic Party will strive for the development of Japan-China
friendly relations with an eye on the 21st century.
</P>
<P>
During the meetings, Li also exchanged views with the three
party leaders on major international issues and other issues of
common concern.
</P>
<P>
Chinese State Councillor and Minister in charge of the State
Science and Technology Commission Song Jian and other ranking
officials accompanying Li on the visit were present at the
meetings. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
