<HEADLINE> S.African Markets Urged to Open up to Zimbabwean </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HARARE, November 12 (Xinhua) -- The Confederation of Zimbabwe
Industries (CZI) once again appealed to neighbouring South Africa
to open up its market to Zimbabwean products and balance trade
between the two countries.
</P>
<P>
CZI President Jonee Blanchfield said in a statement on Tuesday
that Zimbabwe is dismayed that in recent years the share of South
African exports to Zimbabwe had steadily risen, reaching a 38.3
percent increase in 1996, or 10.8 billion Zimbabwe Dollars (800
million U.S. dollars) worth of merchandise. Over the same period,
he said, South Africa imported a paltry two billion Zimbabwe
Dollars (160 million U.S. dollars) or just 9.6 percent of
Zimbabwe's total exports in that year.
</P>
<P>
"We call upon South African business people to urgently open
up and correct the trade imbalance. For the past five years the
economic relations between our two countries have not been as
they should be," she noted.
</P>
<P>
If South Africa continued stifling Zimbabwean exports, the
local market would soon dry up as there would be no income to
purchase their products anymore, the CZI president added.
</P>
<P>
Negotiations for a preferential trade pact have been going on
between Zimbabwe and South Africa since the 1992 expiry of the
1964 agreement.
</P>
<P>
However, South Africa says it remains committed to the
implementation of the trade protocol through a process of
intensive regional negotiations and consultations.
</P>
<P>
Tariffs on textile and trade in a wide range of agricultural
products have been reviewed following an agreement signed last
August. A business promotion exhibition was held recently to
foster partnership among business people from the two countries.
</P>
<P>
Blanchfield has been a consistently fierce critic of South
Africa over its alleged foot dragging in concluding an agreement
that benefits both countries. She added that the practice of
closing down South African subsidiaries in Zimbabwe in favour of
creating warehouses for its products should bring "shame to
moral" South Africans.
</P>
<P>
But she said: "there is still time and scope for change if we
all adopt positive attitudes." 
</P>
</TEXT>
