<HEADLINE> Killing of Americans under Investigation: Pak FM </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ISLAMABAD, November 12 (Xinhua) -- Pakistani Foreign Minister
Gohar Ayub Khan said today the government is looking into the
shooting incident in which four Americans were killed by
unidentified gunmen in Karachi, Pakistan's biggest port city.
</P>
<P>
Deputy Inspector General Malik Iqbal is heading the
investigation into the killings, Gohar said, adding that President
Farooq Leghari and Prime Minister Nawaz Sharif have been informed
of the tragic incident.
</P>
<P>
A statement from the Interior Ministry or the Foreign Ministry,
he said, would be released in the afternoon after further details
are collected about the incident.
</P>
<P>
The four U.S. citizens, who were on a visit in connection with
official work at Union Texas Karachi, were gunned down by
unidentified assailants at around 8:20 a.m. on their way from
Karachi Sheraton Hotel to their office, located about three
kilometers away.
</P>
<P>
According to witnesses, the assailants were in a Red Honda
Civic, which was later found abandoned in a nearby area.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, U.S. embassy officials here when contacted declined
to make any comment on the incident, saying they were still
gathering details.
</P>
<P>
The incident came one day after a 12-member jury declared a
Pakistani national, Aimal Kansi, guilty of killing two CIA agents
and wounding three others in the January, 1993 shooting outside
the Central Intelligence Agency headquarters.
</P>
<P>
The U.S. Embassy on Tuesday warned all American citizens in
Pakistan to be on alert keeping in mind a possible retaliation
after Kansi's conviction in the U.S.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
