<HEADLINE> IAF Trained for Non-Conventional Attack </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JERUSALEM, November 12 (Xinhua) -- In a rare revelation of its
defense capabilities against non-conventional weapons, a senior
Israel Air Force (IAF) officer said IAF pilots and ground crews
are trained with gas masks on and that some hangars are protected
through filters and air-pressure systems.
</P>
<P>
"The most relevant threat against the air force today is from
ground-to-ground missiles, and the missiles are capable of being
armed with both conventional and non-conventional warheads," the
Jerusalem Post newspaper today quoted the IAF's head of behavioral
department Lt.-Col. Arnon as reporting.
</P>
<P>
Arnon said the focus of the Israeli air defense is directly at
Syria, which has hundreds of Scud missiles capable of reaching
most of Israel.
</P>
<P>
Arnon said that NBC (nuclear, biological and chemical) warfare
protection is practiced in all branches of the IAF.
</P>
<P>
"During an anti-aircraft exercise, you can see everyone going
around in NBC protective clothings as they go through the alerts
and firing their missiles under all conditions," Arnon said,
adding that "there is a massive deployment to continue fighting
during an attack."
</P>
<P>
All IAF anti-aircraft batteries along the northern front are
mobile and able to jump from firing station to station on short
notice, he said.
</P>
<P>
He also said the current IAF assumption is that the Arab
states do not have nuclear weapons, and that the aim of the
training of IAF staff is to enable tactical warfare to continue
under biological or chemical attack. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
