<HEADLINE> World Mineral Prices to Pick Up: Zimbabwean </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HARARE, November 12 (Xinhua) -- A senior official from Zimbabwe
Chamber of Mines predicted the world mineral prices will recover
from the current decline and urged the mining industry
to concentrate on improving productivity and quality of
minerals to earn more money for the country.
</P>
<P>
John Nixon, President of the Chamber of Mines said on Tuesday,
local explorations showed that the future of the industry was not
bleak. A number of foreign and local companies were expected to
commission new mines in the near future.
</P>
<P>
But there was need to cut production costs and gear up for
regional and international competition, he added.
</P>
<P>
"We cannot do anything about the falling prices, but we can do
something about our productivity and reduce costs," Nixon noted.
</P>
<P>
The world is currently undergoing an unprecedented slump in
the price of gold, nickel, copper and ferrochrome among others.
</P>
<P>
"What we need is to keep an eye on the trends of events in the
world because we have no god given right to mining since other
countries are also developing their own projects," he said.
</P>
<P>
Nixon predicted that prices would improve, but not before the
depression had claimed casualties in the form of retrenchments.
</P>
<P>
Plummeting world mineral prices, mounting production costs and
high wage bills had thrown the Zimbabwean mining sector into
viability problems, forcing some companies to retrench thousands
of workers or even close operations. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
