<DOCNO> XIE19971112.0220 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-11-12 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Asian Experts Discuss Greenhouse Gas Abatement </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MANILA, November 12 (Xinhua) -- About 100 experts from Asian
governments and multilateral agencies started here today a
three-day workshop on an Asia least-cost greenhouse gas abatement
strategy project.
</P>
<P>
In his opening speech, Asian Development Bank (ADB) President
Mitsuo Sato said that the Asia Least-cost Greenhouse Gas Abatement
Strategy Project was designed to help the participating countries
to meet their commitments made under the U.N. Framework Convention
on Climate Change, he said.
</P>
<P>
"In particular, it helps the countries build up their needed
capacity in environmental protection, prepare national inventories
of greenhouse gas emissions, formulate national greenhouse gas
abatement strategies, and develop country portfolios of investment
projects," he said.
</P>
<P>
According to an ADB report, the 10 million U.S. dollar project
will benefit 12 Asian countries -- Bangladesh, China, India,
Indonesia, Mongolia, Myanmar, Pakistan, the Philippines, the
Republic of Korea, Thailand, Vietnam and the Democratic People's
Republic of Korea.
</P>
<P>
The technical assistance project is co-financed by the ADB and
the Global Environment Facility through the United Nations
Development Program (UNDP), Norway, and the governments of the
participating countries.
</P>
<P>
It is being executed by the ADB in collaboration with UNDP.
</P>
<P>
During the meeting, experts from the 12 Asian countries will
present the results of the country studies, and receive feedback
from a group of international experts and representatives of
multilateral and bilateral organizations active in climate change.
</P>
<P>
Recommendations put forward at the meeting will enable the ADB
to formulate its future strategy on climate change and its impact
in the Asia and Pacific region.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
