<DOCNO> XIE19971112.0222 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-11-12 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> China's Autumn-Winter Sowing Ends </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, November 12 (Xinhua) -- China has sown winter grain
crops on 25.6 million ha of land so far this year, accounting for
85 percent of the planned planting area.
</P>
<P>
Wheat, a principal winter crop, has been planted on 24.3
million ha of land, making up 93 percent of the set area, said an
official from the Ministry of Agriculture.
</P>
<P>
Autumn-Winter sowing in north China is basically completed. Ten
major wheat-growing provinces have sown crops on 16 million ha of
land. The crops planted on time are growing well, the official
said.
</P>
<P>
Winter sowing has started in all southern provinces and is
expected to be completed by the end of the month.
</P>
<P>
China has experienced a rarely seen drought this spring, summer
and autumn, posing a threat to the planting and management of
winter wheat.
</P>
<P>
North China has received no widespread rainfall since
mid-September, and what's worse, the period has been windy with
high temperatures. As a result, soil moisture quickly evaporated.
</P>
<P>
Statistics show that 10 million ha of farmland across China
have been affected by drought. The areas sustaining drought in
north China totalled 7.3 million ha.
</P>
<P>
In Henan Province, a leading wheat producer, 3.4 million ha of
wheat fields badly need water, and wheat on 4.6 million ha of land
in east China's Shandong Province is parched and nearly ruined.
</P>
<P>
A mass campaign to save young crops is spreading in the
country. Hebei, Shandong and Henan provinces have replanted wheat
on 4.1 million ha of land.
</P>
<P>
Wang Wenxue, deputy governor of Shanxi province, urged power
and water conservancy departments to use all water facilities for
irrigation. Jiangsu, Anhui and Hubei provinces have been organized
to fight drought and improve field management. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
