<HEADLINE> Chinese Premier Meets Former Japanese Prime Ministers </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
TOKYO, November 12 (Xinhua)-- Visiting Chinese Premier Li Peng
said here this morning that the nurturing of successors to the
older generation in developing Sino-Japanese friendship now
constitutes a major task for both China and Japan.
</P>
<P>
At a breakfast with five former Japanese prime ministers
Nakasone Yasuhiro, Noburo Takeshita, Toshiki Kaifu, Morihiro
Hosokawa and Tsutomo Hata, Li said China and Japan, both as
countries of major influence in Asia and the world as a whole,
shoulder the task of safeguarding peace and promoting development
at the turn of centuries, and therefore should join efforts in
carrying a long-term stable friendship of good neighborliness
between the two countries into the 21st century.
</P>
<P>
To attain this goal, it is important not only to treasure the
existing Sino-Japanese friendship nurtured by the statesmen of the
old generation of the two countries, but also to develop the
traditional friendship.
</P>
<P>
Li said the five former prime ministers all have made great
contributions to the development of the relations between China
and Japan when they were in office. They have been caring for and
supporting the cause of the Sino-Japanese friendship after they
quit their posts. For this, the Chinese Premier gave high
appraisal and expressed hearty thanks to them.
</P>
<P>
He said he was pleased to meet the five prime ministers who he
described as his "old friends."
</P>
<P>
Li said the relations between China and Japan have gained great
development in the 25 years after the normalization of the
Sino-Japanese diplomatic ties, thanks to the joint efforts of the
governments and people of various circles of the two countries.
</P>
<P>
He expressed the hope that the five former prime ministers will
continue to play an important role in developing the traditional
friendship between China and Japan.
</P>
<P>
At the breakfast, the five former prime minister all expressed
their willingness to continue to work for the further development
of Sino-Japanese friendship. They also expressed their confidence
that the relations between the two countries embrace a broad
prospect for development in the 21st century. 
</P>
</TEXT>
