<HEADLINE> Myanmar, UNICEF Review Country Cooperation Program </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
YANGON, November 12 (Xinhua) -- An annual meeting of the United
Nations Children's Fund (UNICEF) and its Myanmar partner agencies
is being held here to review their country program of cooperation
for 1996-2000.
</P>
<P>
The two-day meeting, which began on Tuesday, highlights not
only major achievements but also key constraints encountered
during the second year of implementation of the five-year country
program, according to today's official paper the New Light of
Myanmar.
</P>
<P>
The review process also involves joint analysis by major
departmental counterparts and UNICEF, of progress achieved in
health and nutrition, education, early childhood development and
water supply and environmental sanitation programs, the report
said.
</P>
<P>
The Myanmar-UNICEF country program of cooperation, which covers
a period from 1996 to 2000, consists of six programs and 17
projects with a total budget of 32.5 million U.S. dollars from
UNICEF general resources and an additional 23.5 million U.S.
dollars to be raised in supplementary funds for the five-year
program cycle. Nearly 43 percent of the combined total is intended
to support the health and nutrition program.
</P>
<P>
The meeting, which is continuing today, is being attended by
diplomats, Myanmar counterparts, national and international NGOs
operating in Myanmar, staff members of UN agencies in Myanmar and
UNICEF staff.  
</P>
</TEXT>
