<HEADLINE> Tanzanian Govt Orders Refugees to Remain in Camp </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
DAR ES SALAAM, November 12 (Xinhua) -- The Tanzanian
government has ordered refugees from other African countries not
to move out of camps as a measure to tighten security of the
surroundings, The Guardian reported today.
</P>
<P>
Speaking at a recent Regional Emergency Management Workshop,
Joseph Rugumyamheto, Principal Secretary in the President's
Office responsible for the Civil Service Department, said the
government found it necessary to take drastic measures to contain
the source of trouble.
</P>
<P>
He said apart from financial burden, the country faces
security problems particularly in areas sheltering the refugees.
There is also the problem of environment degradation, he added.
</P>
<P>
"Unfortunately we have had little support in this regard,
Instead we are blamed by many people while
the international community has kept silent," Rugumyamheto noted.
</P>
<P>
Political turmoil that has taken place in the
neighboring countries over the past few years has created a
massive influx of refugees from Rwanda, Burundi, Somalia, and
other African countries.
</P>
<P>
Rugumyamheto said Tanzania currently hosts more than 800,000
refugees, 200,000 of whom have been given land to cultivate.
</P>
<P>
Currently refugees in camps in the northwestern regions of
Kigoma and Kagera have exceeded 300,000 in number. Others have
settled in different settlements across the country. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
