<HEADLINE> Hungarian, Ukrainian PMs Talk on Bilateral Relations </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BUDAPEST, November 11 (Xinhua) -- Hungarian Prime Minister Horn
Gyula and his Ukraine's counterpart Valery Pusztovoitenko today
held talks on bilateral economic cooperation.
</P>
<P>
Addressing a joint news conference after the talks, Horn said
he and Pusztovoitenko have agreed to reduce or wipe out quotas
that are affecting their bilateral trade as soon as possible.
</P>
<P>
Pusztovoitenko, who arrived here this morning for a two-day
visit, told the press earlier that his current tour aims to
restore their bilateral economic relations to the level that
existed during the former Soviet Union.
</P>
<P>
At the conference, Pusztovoitenko said although Hungary is
Ukraine's third biggest trade partner in the Central and Eastern
Europe following Russia and Belarus, the present level of their
cooperation is still not satisfying.
</P>
<P>
With their current annual trade volume standing at 5.4 billion
U.S. dollars, the two leaders agreed that there is still potential
for further cooperation in the areas such as transportation,
energy, foods and chemical industry.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, representatives of the two governments signed a
package of seven agreements on transportation, economic ties,
trade liberalization, cooperation outside the two countries,
mutual acknowledgement of nuclear accidents and on energy
cooperation. 
</P>
