<BODY>
<HEADLINE> India, Australia to Sign Accord on Removal of </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NEW DELHI, November 12 (Xinhua) -- India and Australia are
close to a bilateral agreement on the removal of quantitative
restrictions (QRs) of import by India, an Indian official said
here today.
</P>
<P>
Australia is reported to have agreed to a six-year phaseout
schedule to begin from April 1 next year. The schedule will be
divided into three phases of three years, two years and one year
respectively.
</P>
<P>
India has agreed to consider around 250 products in the first
phase out of 500 priority items submitted by Australia.
</P>
<P>
India has not given a year-by-year phaseout schedule for each
item, an issue that is obstructing a settlement between India and
the United States. India maintains quantitative curbs on around
2,700 items for imports.
</P>
<P>
India and Australia are expected to sign the agreement next
week. India is also working for a solution with other countries
including the European Union, the official said.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
