<HEADLINE> New Thai Government Attaches Importance to Tourism </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BANGKOK, November 12 (Xinhua) -- Tourism needs an urgent push
while Thailand improves its framework to attract foreign
investment, Supachai Panitchpakdi, who is expected to become chief
economic minister of the new Thai government, told a seminar
entitled "Thai Travel and Tourism: What Next" here Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
The new government's most pressing task was to generate hard
currency earnings to rescue the economy, Supachai was quoted today
by local press as saying.
</P>
<P>
He said this would entail strengthening tourism, promoting
exports and improving the attractiveness of the country to
international investors.
</P>
<P>
Supachai said that while other countries were attempting to
increase promotional privileges to attract foreign investors, the
fall in the value of the baht had already provided good support.
</P>
<P>
To attract investment, the tax structure must be changed, the
foreign shareholding ratio increased, private industrial estates
promoted and flexible entry and residence permits issued to
foreigners, he said.
</P>
<P>
"These things have been discussed before but have never been
seriously implemented. The new Thai government will speed up the
process and make the plan come true as soon as possible," he said.
</P>
<P>
In addition, export manufacturers would need help not only with
cash flow, but also in terms of product quality, meeting both
international standards and environmental concerns, he said.
</P>
<P>
"Next year will be one of major adjustment. We need to
fine-tune our economy for a better future," Supachai said.
</P>
<P>
He said exports and tourism had the highest potential to earn
foreign funds. But the fluctuations in the value of the baht had
caused confusion and businesses, particularly in tourism, should
catch up with the new environment.
</P>
<P>
Although the Tourism Authority of Thailand was preparing to
launch the "Amazing Thailand" 1998-99 campaign, there was a need
for immediate action, Supachai said.
</P>
<P>
"The campaign is good. But when we consider Thailand's need to
repay more than 20 billion US dollars in foreign debt within two
months, more urgent plans are needed. At least the campaign should
tell the world of the excellent value Thailand is offering," he
said.  
</P>
</TEXT>
