<DOCNO> XIE19971112.0247 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-11-12 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Thai Central Bank Eases Cross-Shareholding Limit </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BANGKOK, November 12 (Xinhua) -- The Bank of Thailand Tuesday
eased its cross-shareholding limit and allowed a sound local
financial institution to hold a majority stake in another firm.
</P>
<P>
Under the new rule, a sound local financial institution could
hold a stake of more than 49 percent in another firm for ten year.
</P>
<P>
The new rule will facilitate capital increases in the country's
financial sector, the bank said.
</P>
<P>
To date, the bank previously only allowed a local financial
institution to hold a maximum holding of ten percent in another
firm.
</P>
<P>
Local newspapers said that Bangkok Bank, one of the country's
largest commercial banks, Tuesday hailed the new
cross-shareholding rule as a positive sign to strengthen the
country's financial sector, Saying it will widen the channel for
mergers of commercial banks in the future.
</P>
<P>
Also, the central bank Tuesday reiterated its policy to allow
foreigners to hold a stake of more than 49 percent in a local
financial institution for ten years to help the cash-trapped local
financial institutions to raise capital and improve management.
</P>
<P>
The policy was introduced by the Chavalit Government earlier
this year.
</P>
<P>
Yet, the central bank reserved the right to refuse a foreign
bank to open a full branch in Thailand if it holds a majority
stake in a Thai bank.
</P>
<P>
Local newspapers said that the central bank's latest move was
approved by outgoing finance minister Kosit Panpiemras and
announced before new government ministers come into power.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
