<HEADLINE> Czech Republic Rules out Deployment of Nuclear Weapons </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
PRAGUE, November 11 (Xinhua) -- The Czech Republic will not
allow the deployment of nuclear weapons within its territory, nor
allow any bases to be established there for these weapons, a
senior Czech official said today.
</P>
<P>
The first deputy foreign minister, Karel Kovanda, said in the
newspaper, "The Rights", that after the Czech Republic's entry
into the North Atlantic Treaty Organization (NATO), no foreign
military forces would be deployed in the republic on a permanent
basis.
</P>
<P>
However, small numbers of foreign troops may enter the country
for military exercises or training on a temporary basis, he said.
</P>
<P>
At a NATO summit in Madrid in July, the Czech Republic, along
with Poland and Hungary, was accepted as a new member in the the
first wave to join NATO by 1999, the year of the 50th anniversary
of the Western military alliance.
</P>
<P>
For its own security concerns, Russia is strongly opposed to
NATO's eastward expansion to include former Warsaw Pact countries,
and especially the deployment of nuclear weapons in these
countries. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
