<HEADLINE> Heavy Rains Disrupt Efforts to Control Cholera in </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
COLOMBO, November12 (Xinhua) -- Sri Lanka's efforts to control
the recent outbreak of cholera in Puttalam District, Northwestern
Province have been badly disrupted by prevailing heavy rains and
floods that have inundated part of the region during the past two
weeks.
</P>
<P>
Sources close to the Health Ministry said here today that so
far a total of 122 people have been diagnosed as cholera positive
since the disease began to break out early last month in a coastal
village in Puttalam. Three patients have already died.
</P>
<P>
They said many other people have been affected with a diarrhea
epidemic due to the rains and floods.
</P>
<P>
The local government has launched a massive program to combat
the cholera epidemic despite unsatisfactory weather conditions.
</P>
<P>
About 200 health officials were in the field to help the locals
take preventive measures. Around 400 wells were chlorinated
several times a day.
</P>
<P>
However, the continuous rains along with the floods have
hampered their efforts in bringing the epidemic into control.
Several public toilets built for the locals are overflowing
because of the floods.
</P>
<P>
As a result, the cholera cases are on the rise in Puttalam, the
sources added.
</P>
</TEXT>
