<HEADLINE> Caltex Takes British Petroleum's Business in Thailand </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BANGKOK, November 12 (Xinhua) -- Caltex Oil (Thailand) Ltd has
announced that it had taken over the British Petroleum's (BP's)
entire service station network in Thailand.
</P>
<P>
It was the largest takeover deal in recent years in Thailand's
oil business, local newspapers said today.
</P>
<P>
Caltex announced on Tuesday that it had concluded an agreement
with the BP for the deal worth 1 billion baht (about 27 million US
dollars) to take over its 48 service stations around Thailand.
</P>
<P>
After the takeover, the number of the Caltex firm's service
stations throughout Thailand will increase to 611 and its market
share also increase to about 13.5 percent, the newspapers said.
</P>
<P>
The takeover took place as Thailand is undergoing an economic
slowdown, which has forced many oil service stations to shut down
and pinched the others.
</P>
<P>
The deal is a big gamble amid deep and broad problems facing
the Thai economy, Richard Abrams, managing director of the Caltex
Oil (Thailand) Ltd, was quoted as saying by local newspapers.
</P>
<P>
But he expressed confidence in a long-term recovery of the Thai
economy.
</P>
<P>
The Caltex firm currently is the fourth largest oil marketer in
Thailand, while the BP firm is the sixth.
</P>
<P>
The Petroleum Authority of Thailand currently is the largest,
which captured 27.3 percent of the Thai market during January and
August this year. It is followed by Shell and Esso.  
</P>
</TEXT>
