<HEADLINE> Romanians, Czechs Seek Closer Military Cooperation </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BUCHAREST, November 11 (Xinhua) -- Romania and the Czech
Republic announced today that they will resume talks on military
cooperation next year,
</P>
<P>
The announcement was made by Romanian Defense Minister Victor
Babiuc and his Czech counterpart, Miloslav Vyborny, at a joint
press conference.
</P>
<P>
Babiuc and the visiting Czech minister, who arrived here for a
two-day stay, have discussed bilateral relations and the situation
in the Balkan region.
</P>
<P>
Vyborny said his country would support Romania's entry into the
North Atlantic Treaty Organization (NATO), and both sides would
take measures to ensure the implementation of a military
cooperation agreement signed in 1995.
</P>
<P>
On Monday, Romanian Prime Minister Victor Ciorbea voiced his
satisfaction about development in military relations between the
two nations. 
</P>
