<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Cuba Encourages Industrial Investment </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HAVANA, November 11 (Xinhua) -- The Cuban government has
encouraged foreign investments in the industrial sectors in newly
established duty free zones, a Cuban official said today.
</P>
<P>
Octavio Castilla, director of the national office for the
zones, said the Cuban government favors foreign countries setting
up their companies in the duty free areas.
</P>
<P>
He said 20 percent of foreign companies in Cuba were
established in duty free areas and the percentage was expected to
rise.
</P>
<P>
Under Cuban Law, 75 percent of trade in these areas will be for
foreign markets and 25 percent will be directed to domestic
markets.
</P>
<P>
Cuba set up two duty free areas near Havana port and the
airport in May, and a third was opened last week in the town of
Mariel, about 60 kilometers west of Havana. 
</P>
</TEXT>
