<HEADLINE> Chile Adjusts Copper Prices </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
SANTIAGO, November 11 (Xinhua) -- Chile's Copper Commission
(Cochilco) has adjusted its previous forecast for the average
price of copper per pound for the year, because of difficulties in
quotations during the second half of 1997.
</P>
<P>
The list of prices, published today by the local press, puts
the average price for 1997 between 1.03 and 1.05 U.S. dollars a
pound, a price similar to the 1996 close of 1.039 dollars.
</P>
<P>
Over the first half, Cochilco estimated the copper price at
1.00 to 1.05 dollars per pound, but the forecast was upgraded due
to a steady demand, registering average prices above 1.10 dollars
per pound.
</P>
<P>
Acknowledging those facts, the authority estimated that the
price of copper would approach 1.08 dollars per pound.
</P>
<P>
Nonetheless, copper's price started to fall, caused by
depressed economic activities in the northern hemisphere. The
price of the metal plunged Monday to 0.886 dollars, the lowest
since October 30, 1996.
</P>
<P>
Because of the current conditions of the market, Cochilco had
to readjust downwards the average price estimate for this
year. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
