<HEADLINE> Pension, Wage Reforms Deadlocked in Ukraine </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
KIEV, November 11 (Xinhua) -- Ukraine's pension and wage
reforms have run into a deadlock following President Leonid
Kuchma's rejection of an attempt by the leftist-dominated
parliament to raise the minimum pension on Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
Kuchma said the decision of the Supreme Soviet (the Ukrainian
parliament) to raise the minimum pension to 70.9 gryvnas (about 38
U.S. dollars) a month would bankrupt the country. The Supreme
Soviet passed the legislation to raise minimum pension on June 4
this year.
</P>
<P>
The president said the government would have to pay 25.6
billion gryvnas (13.7 billion dollars) to the State Pension Fund
(SPF) if the legislation came into effect. In fact, the SPF is
expected to pay 9.2 billion gryvnas (4.9 billion dollars) in
pensions.
</P>
<P>
At present, the average pension in Ukraine is 45 gryvnas (24
dollars) for the 17 million pensioners. Ukraine has a population
of 51.6 million.
</P>
<P>
Kuchma also vetoed a law to raise the minimum wage which the
parliament passed on October 15. The law would raise the minimum
wage from 15 gryvnas (eight dollars) to 73.7 gryvnas (about 39
dollars) a month after January 1, 1998.
</P>
<P>
He said the parliament failed to state the source of funds for
the increases since Ukraine's economy had shown no sign of
recovery, even for the coming year.
</P>
<P>
Observers claim left-wing lawmakers tried to please voters by
passing these two laws as the parliamentary elections
approached. At a time when the government was unable to pay its
workers properly, the legislation would gain support from voters
and force the president into a very difficult "corner". 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19971112.0268 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-11-12 </DATE_TIME>
