<HEADLINE> IMF Chief Upbeat On Indonesia's Economic Reforms </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JAKARTA, November 12 (Xinhua) -- The International Monetary
Fund (IMF) said Indonesia would eventually recover from the
current economic downturn after it fully implemented the
IMF-backed reform program.
</P>
<P>
The statement was made by IMF Managing Director Michel
Camdessus here last night upon his arrival at the Jakarta Airport.
</P>
<P>
The IMF chief's two-day visit showed his support for the
country's reforms to tackle the monetary crisis, local press
reported today.
</P>
<P>
"Of course this year, or possibly next year, will still be
difficult. But I'm personally confident, if this program is fully
implemented, it will have all the potential to put your country
back on a very good track, with solid and even more sustainable
growth," Camdessus was quoted as saying.
</P>
<P>
On the Indonesian government's determination to dismantle the
National Logistic Agency's trading monopoly on several commodities
and close 16 ailing banks, the IMF chief described the program as
the government's effort "to strengthen the basis for growth and
strengthen the country's capacity to react to every turbulence in
the financial market."
</P>
<P>
"This is the program of your country, designed by your
authorities, of course, with the support of the IMF, the World
Bank and the Asian Development Bank," Camdessus said.
</P>
<P>
The IMF announced an aid package for Indonesia last month of 23
billion U.S. dollars to help the country implement its reform
program to face the economic and monetary crisis.
</P>
<P>
Camdessus met with Indonesian economic officials yesterday
evening to discuss the implementation of the reform program. he
was scheduled to have a breakfast this morning with business
people and bankers before meeting with President Soeharto,
official sources said.  
</P>
</TEXT>
