<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Philippine Government to Appeal Against Supreme Court </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MANILA, November 12 (Xinhua) -- The Philippine government has
decided to file a motion for reconsideration of last week's
Supreme Court ruling nullifying the oil deregulation law and to
pursue filing of a new bill.
</P>
<P>
The government had agreed to file an appeal to prevent the
court decision, which was scheduled to take effect on November 21,
from being final and executory, local press reports quoted Finance
Secretary Roberto de Ocampo as saying.
</P>
<P>
The High Tribunal last week struck down the nine-month-old oil
deregulation law as unconstitutional, saying some of its
provisions encouraged the country's three dominant oil companies
to gain monopoly.
</P>
<P>
The oil deregulation law, which took effect in February this
year, encouraged firms to invest in refineries in the country and
firms that were just importing and selling finished products were
charged higher tariffs.
</P>
<P>
The court said forcing firms to choose between investing huge
amounts in refineries or paying higher tariffs amounted to a
restriction on free trade and violated the intention of the law.
</P>
<P>
De Ocampo said the government would file a new bill that would
leave the tariff setting to President Fidel Ramos.
</P>
<P>
He said the government still favored setting higher tariffs on
finished petroleum products but would be willing to give
concession to new players.
</P>
<P>
Currently, crude imports have a tariff of three percent, while
imported finished products have a rate of seven percent.
</P>
<P>
Ramos has urged the Congress to speed up the passage of a new
oil deregulation law to save the country's liberalized oil
industry.
</P>
<P>
House Speaker Jose de Venecia said he expected Congress to pass
a new oil reform law before Christmas.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19971112.0278 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-11-12 </DATE_TIME>
