<HEADLINE> Xinhua World News Summary at 0100 GMT, November 12 </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BAGHDAD -- Iraqi Foreign Minister Mohammed Saeed al-Sahhaf said
here Tuesday that Iraqi stance on the American U2 spy plane will
remain unchanged, asserting that Iraq will fire at any aircraft
threatening its national security.
</P>
<P>
Speaking at a news conference, Sahhaf said that a number of
U.S. officials were intentionally portraying to public opinion
that Iraqi President Saddam Hussein was seeking to create a crisis
by threatening to shoot down the U.S. plane that resumed flights
over Iraq Monday.
</P>
<P>
Rejecting the charge, he said the issue is not that of creating
a crisis, but a question of defending the Iraqi people's rights.
</P>
<P>
In Washington, U.S. President Bill Clinton on Tuesday said
Iraqi President Saddam Hussein has no right to prevent U.N.
weapons inspection teams from working and called on the
international community to demand that they be allowed to do their
job.
</P>
<P>
JERUSALEM -- Thousands of people attended a memorial ceremony
at the Zion Square here Tuesday night to commemorate the second
Hebrew anniversary of the assassination of Israel Prime Minister
Yitzhak Rabin.
</P>
<P>
The mourners, who gathered earlier in the evening in front of
the Prime Minister's residence, marched peacefully in the streets
of Jerusalem leading to the downtown Square.
</P>
<P>
AMMAN -- The first two Israeli planes landed Tuesday at the
airport of Aqaba, Jordan's Red Sea resort, under an agreement
signed between the two countries last August.
</P>
<P>
An El Al plane with 189 passengers on board flew from St.
Petersburg, Russia and the other from Frankfurt, Germany, Jordan's
official news agency Petra reported.
</P>
<P>
About 60 passengers, mostly Israelis, were driven in bus to
Israel's Eilat through the Wadi Araba crossing.
</P>
<P>
According to the aviation agreement, flights heading for
Israel's Eilat may land at the Aqaba Airport in a period of four
months to ease the crowdedness of the Eilat Airport.
</P>
<P>
LONDON -- New Irish President Mary McAleese has promised to do
her best to help bring a long lasting peace to the British-ruled
Northern Ireland, said reports from Dublin Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
Speaking in an inauguration address at the Dublin Castle,
McAleese, who is the first ever Irish head of state born in
Northern Ireland, said that the theme of her presidency would be
building bridges between conflicting communities. 
</P>
</TEXT>
