<HEADLINE> Sampras Upset, Rafter and Chang Win </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BONN, November 11 (Xinhua) -- World No. 1 Pete Sampras of the
United States gave the way to Spaniard Carlos Moya at the opening
match of the ATP Tour World Championship in Hanover on Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
Sampras, seeking his fourth title in the season-ending event,
made a unusual total of 50 unforced errors and lost to the
21-year-old Spaniard 6-3, 6-7 (4-7), 6-2.
</P>
<P>
"It's not the start I wanted, but I'm not out of it," said
Sampras.
</P>
<P>
Moya's victory was a revenge for his straight-set loss to the
American in the Australian Open final early this year.
</P>
<P>
Sampras will take on Patrick Rafter and Greg Rusedski, who are
both ranked higher than No. 7 Moya.
</P>
<P>
In a fight of two brightest stars of 1997, world No. 3 Rafter
beat Rusedski 4-6, 6-3, 6-4, repeating his victory over the Briton
in the U.S. Open final.
</P>
<P>
Rusedski, ranked No. 5, is the first British player in the
tournament, while Rafter is the first Australian since 1987.
</P>
<P>
In the other group, World No. 2 Michael Chang fought back four
set points in the first set and beat Sergi Bruguera 7-6 (10-8),
6-2.
</P>
<P>
Chang, making his sixth showing in the event, didn't give his
rival a chance in the second set after surviving the first.
</P>
<P>
The 3.3 million U.S. dollars tournament attracts the top eight
players in the world, with them to be split into two groups. The
top two from each group advance to the semi-finals. 
</P>
</TEXT>
