<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Waigel: Germany will Meet Euro Criteria </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BONN, November 11 (Xinhua) -- German Finance Minister Theo
el today said that Germany will be able to meet the budgetary
requirement of the planned single European currency despite an
expected huge shortfall in tax revenues in 1997.
</P>
<P>
Waigel's remarks came after a government-appointed tax estimate
group released its latest projections earlier today, saying that
Germany would face a shortfall of 17.3 billion marks (10 billion
U.S. dollars) in tax revenues in 1997 and even a bigger one of
22.4 billion marks (13 billion dollars) in 1998.
</P>
<P>
Thanks to already planned cuts in job-creation subsidies, a
spending freeze, further privatization of state-own companies and
delaying repayment of national debts inherited from the former
East Germany, Germany's budget deficit for 1997 would not
overshoot the previously agreed level of 71.2 billion marks (42
billion dollars) and would even be reduced to 57 billion (33
billion dollars) next year, Waigel said.
</P>
<P>
"We will meet the Maastricht Treaty criteria for both years,"
he said.
</P>
<P>
Under the EU Maastricht Treaty, EU states are required, among
other things, to bring their budget deficit to less than three
percent of gross domestic product (GDP) in order to join the
single currency, the Euro. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
