<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Iraqi Stance on US U2 plane Unchanged: FM </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BAGHDAD, November 11 (Xinhua) -- Iraqi Foreign Minister
Mohammed Saeed al-Sahhaf said here today that Iraqi stance on the
American U2 spy plane will remain unchanged, asserting that Iraq
will fire at any aircraft threatening its national security.
</P>
<P>
Sahhaf made the remark at a news conference this evening. He
said that a number of U.S. officials were intentionally portraying
to public opinion that Iraqi President Saddam Hussein was seeking
to create a crisis by threatening to shoot down the U.S. plane that
resumed flights over Iraq Monday.
</P>
<P>
Rejecting the charge, he said the issue is not that of creating
a crisis, but a question of defending the Iraqi people's rights.
</P>
<P>
Iraq would defend its rights in the face of a possible
U.S. military "aggression." This is not the first time that
America is committing aggression against Iraq, he added.
</P>
<P>
Iraq has repeatedly accused the U.S. weapons inspectors of
espionage and has threatened to shoot down the U2 plane used by
the inspectors.
</P>
<P>
Sahhaf called for refraining from making a linkage between the
issue of sanctions and that of banned weapons. He indicated that
Iraq had suggested that the U.N. Special Commission on dismantling
Iraqi weapons of mass destruction be composed of all the five
standing members of the Security Council.
</P>
<P>
The suggestion is aimed at making the commission a neutral one,
preventing it from misleading the public opinion by saying that
Iraq hides banned weapons, he said.
</P>
<P>
He complained that the Security Council does not heed Iraq, but
only listens to the special commission.
</P>
<P>
He expressed hope that the Security Council might find a way
for dialog with Iraq on the current crisis. He said Iraq finds
itself in a position where there is no hope whatsoever for the
lifting of the U.N. sanctions.
</P>
<P>
The U.N. sanctions imposed after Iraqi invasion of Kuwait in
1990 cannot be lifted until the inspectors verify that Iraq has
eliminated all its weapons of mass destruction.
</P>
<P>
"We hoped," the Iraqi foreign minister said, "that the other
side would respect its commitments towards Iraq as we did respect
our commitments toward the international resolutions."
</P>
<P>
Sahhaf concluded his statements by underlining Monday's
American provocation by sending a U2 aircraft to overfly Iraqi
airspace, hoping that this mistake would not be repeated. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19971112.0295 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-11-11 21:39 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Iran, Bahrain to Reaccredit Ambassadors </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ABU DHABI, November 11 (Xinhua) -- Iran and Bahrain today
agreed to reaccredit their ambassadors to each other, a signal
for the return of the two countries' bilateral relations to
normal track.
</P>
<P>
The decision was announced after the meeting between Iranian
Foreign Minister Kamal Kharrazi and his Bahraini counterpart
Sheikh Mohammed bin Mubarak al-Khalifa in the Bahraini capital
of Manama this afternoon, the Bahraini news agency reported.
</P>
<P>
The Bahraini foreign minister told reporters that during their
 meeting, he and Kharrazi "exchanged views on...improving ties,
restructuring trust and removing obstacles" between the two
countries and they agreed to resend ambassadors to each other.
</P>
<P>
Bahrain and Iran recalled their ambassadors in May last year
after a row on Bahrain's unrest. Manama accused Iran of being
behind the 19-month wave of riots in Bahrain. Tehran denied the
accusation.
</P>
<P>
After more than one year of tense relations, Bahrain
expressed welcome to the Iranian foreign minister's visit.
</P>
<P>
Khalifa said that Kharrazi's visit is "a signal from the new
Iranian authorities" to mend fences with Bahrain and other Gulf
states.
</P>
<P>
Kaharazzi arrived in Bahrain today on a two-day official visit
as part of his tour to the Gulf region to improve its strained
ties with its Arab neighbors.
</P>
<P>
Iran has been trying to reach out to its Arab Gulf neighbours
across the Gulf since Iran's President Mohammad Khatami formed a
new government in August.
</P>
<P>
The Iranian foreign minister's tour comes one month before the
December 9-11 meeting of the Organization of the Islamic
Conference (OIC) in Iranian capital Tehran.
</P>
<P>
Iran feverishly hopes to make the meeting an unprecedented
gathering of foreign dignitaries. Around 50 heads of states,
including Bahrain, have been invited to the convention.
</P>
<P>
Khalifa said that during his talks with the visiting Iranian
foreign minister, they also discussed the upcoming conference.
</P>
<P>
Bahrain is the third leg of Kharrazi's tour which has taken
him to Saudi Arabia and Kuwait, and will also take him to Qatar,
Oman and the UAE. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19971112.0296 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-11-12 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Sudan Launches Counter-Sanction on US </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
KHARTOUM, November 11 (Xinhua) -- In a counter-measure against
U.S. economic sanctions, Sudan said today it will bar exports of
Arab gum to the United States.
</P>
<P>
The Speaker of the Sudanese National Assembly (parliament)
Hassan Abdulla al Turabi made the announcement when addressing a
number of officials in Ad-Daher, the River Nile Province, some 500
kilometers north of Khartoum.
</P>
<P>
He expressed confidence that the United States would kneel down
before Sudan and ask it to give the U.S. oil firms concessions in
the country.
</P>
<P>
The Sudanese decision is of the same kind as the new
U.S. economic sanctions, he pointed out, urging the Sudanese
people to boycott the U.S.-made products.
</P>
<P>
The United States imports some 20,000 tonnes of Arab gum from
Sudan annually, or a quarter of its total need.
</P>
<P>
The Sudanese decision is expected to harm 63 U.S. firms that
import the Arab gum from Sudan and will have to buy it from
European countries against higher prices.
</P>
<P>
Washington announced early this month new and extensive
economic sanctions against Sudan for its alleged support for
international terrorism and human rights record. The sanctions
include freezing all Sudanese assets in the U.S. and barring
U.S. investment, bank loans and trade on selected items. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19971112.0297 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-11-12 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Clinton: U.N. Inspectors "Must Get Back to Work" </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, November 11 (Xinhua) -- President Bill Clinton on
Tuesday said Iraqi President Saddam Hussein has no right to
prevent U.N. weapons inspection teams from working and called on
the international community to demand that they be allowed to do
their job.
</P>
<P>
"Saddam's efforts to rebuild his weapons of mass destruction
and his interference with the United Nations inspectors who are
keeping him from doing so are unacceptable," Clinton said at
Veterans Day ceremonies at Arlington National Cemetery in Virginia.
</P>
<P>
"They are doing what they should be doing," he said. "They
must get back to work and the international community must
demand it," he added.
</P>
<P>
Clinton said the inspectors "since 1991, have discovered and
destroyed more weapons of mass destruction potential than was
destroyed in Iraq during the entire Gulf War."
</P>
<P>
The Iraqis said American inspectors in U.N. weapons inspection
teams were gathering sensitive intelligence informations in their
country under the guise of working for U.N. inspections.
</P>
<P>
They demanded that Americans leave the U.N. weapons
inspection teams and asked the United Nations to re-compose
these inspection teams before they re-start their work. 
</P>
</TEXT>
