<DATE_TIME> 1997-11-12 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Greek Equities End at Seven-Month Low </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ATHENS, November 11 (Xinhua) -- Greek equities today plunged to
their lowest levels since April 24 with the general index losing
5.85 percent to end at 1,377.76 points.
</P>
<P>
Traders said that the market looked vulnerable ahead of
presentation of the 1998 budget by the end of the month with
sentiment bearish because of rumors that commercial banks plan to
raise interest rates.
</P>
<P>
Sector indices ended sharply lower. Banks suffered the heaviest
losses with a 6.54 percent drop reflecting market worries over the
profitability of the sector following recent international
financial turmoil.
</P>
<P>
Trading was heavy with turnover at 28.8 billion drachmas (about
1.05 billion U.S. dollars).
</P>
<P>
Insurance fell 3.15 percent, leasing dropped 4.56 percent,
investment ended 6.16 percent down, construction eased 6.28
percent, industrials fell 4.49 percent, miscellaneous ended 5.21
percent off and holding lost 6.40 percent.
</P>
<P>
The parallel market index for small cap companies ended 5.09
percent lower.
</P>
<P>
Decliners led advancers by 220 to 9 with another 7 issues
unchanged. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
